<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / BCCI auditors face Dollars 8bn suit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRICE WATERHOUSE and Ernst &amp; Young, the leading accountancy firms, are to be
sued for an estimated Dollars 8bn (Pounds 4.6bn) for alleged negligence and
breach of contract in their audit of Bank of Credit and Commerce
International.
BCCI's liquidators, led by Mr Brian Smouha, of the accounting firm Touche
Ross, will in the next few days serve their statement of claim in their case
against PW and Ernst &amp; Young.
The damages claim relates to writs against the two accounting firms issued
by the liquidators in the UK high court in March.
The writs allege negligence, breach of duty and breach of contract relating
to BCCI audits for 1985 and 1986. The damages claim, thought to be a record
for any claim in the UK, relates to losses suffered by BCCI since 1986.
Ernst &amp; Young and PW will contest the actions and are confident of their
legal position.
After serving the statement of claim on the two firms, the liquidators,
which are acting for the holding company and its Cayman Island and
Luxembourg subsidiaries, are not obliged to make the details public. They
have not decided whether to disclose the huge sum claimed, pending the start
of a trial. Last night Mr Smouha refused to comment.
Until 1987, PW and Ernst &amp; Young both acted as auditors to the BCCI group of
companies. PW then took sole responsibility for auditing BCCI's businesses.
BCCI was closed by the Bank of England in July 1991, after it discovered
evidence of a huge fraud in the bank.
Accountants have been facing a growing number of ever larger legal claims in
recent years in connection with their role as auditors to collapsed
companies.
As a result, the accountants have found it increasingly expensive to
purchase insurance to cover the risk of such action.
</TEXT>
