<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / Recession claims 4,500 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK recession claimed more than 4,500 jobs yesterday while new figures
confirmed that the number of company failures is still accelerating and
about to break all records.
With industry still awaiting significant signs of recovery, Dun &amp;
Bradstreet, the business information company, said that more than 46,000
companies collapsed in the first nine months of this year - almost equalling
the number of failures in 1991.
The company warned that the recession looked poised to 'devastate' small
businesses.
Reacting to the latest redundancies, Mr John Edmonds, general secretary of
the GMB general workers' union, claimed that unemployment was now 'running
out of control', with Britain heading towards 'the worst winter for
unemployment in living memory'. Mr Bill Jordan, president of the Amalgamated
Engineering and Electrical Union, said there was 'a jobs avalanche on the
move'.
The biggest jobs blow yesterday was the announcement that about 2,000 jobs
will go at the government's Defence Research Agency, set up in April last
year to make the government's defence research activities more cost
effective. The job cuts, to achieve savings of Pounds 90m a year, will take
two years to complete.
In the private sector, up to 1,800 jobs are to be shed by Sears, the UK
retail and mail order group. In the latest reorganisation of its British
Shoe Corporation business, the group plans to close 350 shops - which trade
under high street names such as Dolcis and Saxone - over the next three
years.
Northern Telecom, the Canadian telecommunications company, is to cut 426
jobs, most of them in Northern Ireland. The company blamed the recession.
Pirelli Cables, the UK subsidiary of the Italian tyre and cable company, is
to dismiss nearly 300 workers at plants in Hampshire and Newport, Wales. The
company blamed falling demand.
Independent Television News said it was shedding 112 technical support and
administration staff as part of a cost-cutting programme. The company will
ask for volunteers but said compulsory redundancies could not be ruled out.
