<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / International Bonds: Denmark produces tightly-priced Dollars
500m issue to top up its foreign reserves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DENMARK turned to the Eurobond market yesterday to help top up its foreign
exchange reserves, producing an extremely tightly-priced Dollars 500m issue
that brought sharp intakes of breath from some underwriters.
The lead-managers, though, reported that most of the paper was placed during
the day, apparently disproving a view that borrowing costs in the
international bond market would rise sharply after the events of recent
days.
The five-year issue had attracted bids at a yield of over 45 basis points
above US Treasuries, but Daiwa won the mandate at a bid below 30. At launch,
the bid spread was 28.2 basis points over Treasuries.
Even the lead-managers said this was some four or five basis points below
the market clearing level, though other banks said the yield should have
been up to 10 basis points higher.
Demand was said to be strong from the Far East, with more than half the
bonds sold being placed there overnight.
Daiwa said it and the two co-leads - Westdeutsche Landesbank and Warburg -
had placed some 80 per cent of the Dollars 420m of bonds they had
underwritten between them. That was a higher proportion than most others had
thought possible given tight pricing.
After breaking syndicate, Daiwa stood behind the issue, picking up some
bonds as the yield spread rose to around 32 basis points. That appeared
comfortable with the break-even for the syndicate at around 34 basis points,
however, and the spread tightened later to under 30.
The deal drew a mixture of grudging support and disbelief from other
bankers. Even for a borrower renowned for squeezing every last basis point
out of the market, the pricing was seen as very tight. Other bankers said
only once the price had found its final level in the secondary market could
the deal be judged.
</TEXT>
