<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / International Company News: Chairman of Skanska resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE chairman and chief executive of Skanska, Scandinavia's largest
construction and property group, resigned yesterday, accepting his share of
responsibility for the estimated SKr1.2bn (Dollars 222.2m) losses suffered
by the company as a result of alleged unauthorised foreign exchange
speculation and the high Swedish interest rates.
Mr Lars-Ove Hakansson, head of Skanska since 1986, said he was leaving
immediately. He will be replaced as chairman by Mr Percy Barnevik, chief
executive of Asea Brown-Boveri, the Swedish-Swiss engineering conglomerate,
who has been on Skanska's board for the past six years and became
vice-chairman in 1991.
Mr Sven-Eric Hersvall will remain as Skanska's president but the post of
chief executive will be subsumed in the organisation.
The sudden change at the top of the company followed an emergency board
meeting yesterday. 'Skanska is a well-run company strong on the contracting
business side with a number of industrial companies and a good stock of real
estate companies', said Mr Barnevik. It was important to concentrate harder
on key operations and restore confidence in the company, he said.
Mr Hakansson's abrupt departure from Skanska follows the dismissal of the
head of the group's financial subsidiary earlier in the month for alleged
currency speculation during the summer that cost Skanska an estimated
SKr1bn.
</TEXT>
