<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / International Company News: Svenska Handelsbanken drops 80%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SVENSKA Handelsbanken, Sweden's third largest commercial bank, reported
yesterday that operating profits fell 80 per cent to SKr441m (Dollars 81m)
in the first eight months of 1992 from the comparable period last year,
writes Chris Brown-Humes in Stockholm.
Credit losses rose 86 per cent to SKr3.94bn as a result of the protracted
recession and the deteriorating property market. The losses correspond to
2.1 per cent of total lending at the end of August.
The bank made a loss of SKr223m in the second four months, after reporting
operating profits of SKr664m in the first four months of the year. This was
because the latest period saw a further SKr615m of losses stemming from
loans to Gamlestaden, the collapsed finance company.
Svenska Handelsbanken's total share of losses relating to Gamlestaden now
exceeds SKr1.1bn.
</TEXT>
