FT  30 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Winding up petitions add new twist to
Blystad bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DISAGREEMENT between directors of the Blystad Group over the conditions of
a Pounds 7.5m paper bid has taken a new twist with the issue of winding up
petitions against two companies connected with three of the directors, all
members of the Norwegian Blystad family.
The petitions are part of a campaign by directors outside the family to
recover a Dollars 3.9m (Pounds 2.3m) loan to Sokana Industries, which is
controlled by the family. Sokana and the South Pacific Banking Corporation
are the subject of the petitions.
Three Blystad brothers holding 65 per cent of the loss-making Blystad, which
owns KCA Drilling, the UK independent offshore oil service company, have
accepted the 5.4p-a-share bid from Abbot Holdings, a private company set up
by Mr Alasdair Locke.
The non-family board members, including the managing director and finance
director, and Henry Ansbacher, financial advisers, oppose the offer because
of a potential conflict of interest over the loan from Blystad to Sokana
Industries.
Abbot's approach to the loan, set out in the press release announcing the
bid, is not to take any 'precipitate' enforcement action, although it does
not rule out the loan being recovered at a later date.
