<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Sears continues retailing drive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SEARS' drive to focus on retailing and mail order may be finalised this year
with the disposal of its Galliford house-building business.
Mr Geoffrey Maitland Smith, chairman, said this could incur a further
extraordinary charge this year on top of the Pounds 84m included in the
interim results. All but Pounds 2m of this sum was for the shedding of men's
wear through the sale, announced last week, of Fosters and Your Price to
management for Pounds 1.
Galliford used to contribute up to Pounds 30m a year in trading profits, but
the group decided to give it up in July 1990. The only provision made then
was for the carrying costs 'to avoid it impacting on the profit and loss
account'.
The portfolio had since been run down from Pounds 109m to Pounds 58m and
Pounds 11m cash was released in the first half of this year. The original
plan was 'to develop it out by July 1994'. The group was considering whether
to dispose of it within the next six months, possibly via a management
buy-out.
Housing sales, 'tax planning' and cash generation had helped reduce net debt
by Pounds 75m in July 1991 to Pounds 133m this time, gearing of 11.3 per
cent. Net interest costs, however, rose to Pounds 8m (Pounds 7.3m) as the
amount capitalised in Galliford was cut from Pounds 4.9m to Pounds 2.8m.
Recession finally caught up with the home shopping division, where trading
profit fell from Pounds 15.3m to Pounds 11.9m on sales of Pounds 264.9m
(Pounds 249.8m). 'It hit the wall quickly last year leaving a cost
overhang,' said Mr Liam Strong, chief executive.
The subsequent cuts had included 300 jobs, 6 per cent of the workforce. The
annual savings would amount to between Pounds 3m and Pounds 5m.
Sears paid Pounds 477m for the Freemans mail order business in 1988 and
failed in its bid to expand it last year by buying Grattan from Next.
Mr Strong said he hoped to push Freemans' annual trading profit up to more
than Pounds 30m.
In speciality retailing, women's wear was the biggest contributor with
Pounds 6.5m (Pounds 5.6m) profit on sales of Pounds 243.6m (Pounds 214m).
Miss Selfridge - which claims 20 per cent of the disco clothing market - and
Wallis, aimed at 25 to 35-year-olds, had performed strongly.
Selfridges department store in London, which has a division to itself,
enhanced its productivity in a period of sluggish sales caused by a lack of
tourists. Trading profit rose to Pounds 5.5m (Pounds 4.9m) on sales of
Pounds 94.6m (Pounds 92.7m).
</TEXT>
