FT  30 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Surrey Group back in the red
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SURREY GROUP, the USM-quoted bookmaker, returned to losses in the second
half of the year to March 31. And with further substantial losses expected
in the present six months it is changing its acquisition strategy in order
to cut debts.
At its flotation in 1989 it intended to reach critical mass for economies of
scale by buying betting offices. However, the chairman said that the level
of borrowing had become excessive compared with its ability to service it in
the light of poor trading.
In the year to the end of March pre-tax profits were Pounds 5,000 against
losses of Pounds 216,000 in the previous year. Interim profits had been
Pounds 117,000.
From turnover of Pounds 49.6m (Pounds 35.8m) operating profits were Pounds
766,000 including Pounds 611,000 from the sale of betting offices and other
operating income.
An extraordinary charge of Pounds 398,000, relating to the company's former
cricket centres which went into liquidation before the full consideration
had been paid by the new owners, left the retained loss at Pounds 295,000
(Pounds 404,000).
Earnings per share came out at 0.07p, helped by a tax credit of Pounds
98,000 (Pounds 65,000), against losses of 0.15p. The final dividend is being
passed. Last time there was a single final payment of 0.05p.
