FT  30 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Higher interest charges push down Prestwick
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESTWICK HOLDINGS, the Strathclyde-based manufacturer of printed circuit
boards used in the computer, electronics and telecommunications industries,
yesterday reported a decline in full-year pre-tax profits, despite a 20 per
cent increase in turnover.
Pre-tax profits slipped to Pounds 91,000 in the year to July 31 compared
with Pounds 109,000 last time, mainly reflecting sharply higher net interest
charges which grew to Pounds 455,000 (Pounds 64,000) as the group raised its
borrowings to help fund acquisitions and internal investments.
The company is dipping into reserves to pay an unchanged final dividend of
1p per share, which with the interim dividend, will maintain the total at
1.5p. The board said it felt justified in recommending the payment out of
reserves because of the prospects for the group.
Turnover increased to Pounds 30.4m (Pounds 25.3m), and profits before tax
and interest grew to Pounds 546,000 (Pounds 173,000), after charging
exceptional items of Pounds 76,000 (Pounds 373,000.)
During the year Prestwick completed four acquisitions, Band Electronics,
Prestwick-GTN, Electroconnect and Northumbria Circuits, at a total cost of
Pounds 704,000.
Following the acquisition of Electroconnect in October last year Prestwick
spent Pounds 3m on a capital investment programme on advanced design and
manufacturing technology designed to enhance the group's ability to meet its
customers' needs from initial design concept to volume manufacturing.
Mr Wayne Osman, chief executive, said the company had invested about Pounds
6m during the year, and had moved from zero borrowings to net borrowings of
about Pounds 4m at year-end.
After allowing for a Pounds 15,000 tax credit (nil) and Pounds 216,000
(Pounds 218,000) in preference share dividends the group posted an increased
loss of Pounds 110,033 (Pounds 108,780), equivalent to losses per share of
0.5p (same).
