FT  30 SEP 92 / Jefferson Smurfit down by 20% as low prices take toll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JEFFERSON Smurfit, Ireland's largest industrial group, yesterday reported
pre-tax profits for the first six months to July 31 down 20 per cent from
IPounds 75.1m (Pounds 78.33m) to IPounds 60m. Results were below
expectations and the company's shares fell 11 per cent from 257p to 228p.
Mr Dermot Smurfit, chairman and chief executive of Smurfit Continental
Europe, said the results were disappointing. The group was continuing to
struggle with low prices while the industry suffered a period of deflation,
he explained.
He stressed, however, that the company was a strong ship in turbulent
waters. In particular, the balance sheet was in good shape with net cash of
about IPounds 200m.
Operating cash flow was positive at IPounds 26m.
The group remains on the lookout for acquisitions, he said. But although the
industry's earnings were falling, transaction prices had not dropped to a
level at which the company was interested. Any acquisitions would be funded
in cash or through bank borrowings, rather than a rights issue, he added.
The results were achieved on turnover up 7 per cent, from IPounds 611m to
IPounds 654m. Earnings per share fell 22 per cent from 11.7p to 9.1p on a
part capitalisation basis. The company recently had a one-for-one share
issue.
Margins had been suffering in the US and Europe, said Mr Smurfit. Poor
demand and prices had meant the US and Canadian businesses' profits before
tax fell from a profit of IPounds 728,000 to a loss of IPounds 4m for the
six months. The group has restructured the borrowings of its JFC/CCA
American subsidiary, which should increase its profits by Dollars 23m
(Pounds 13.4m) for the full year.
In continental Europe profits fell from IPounds 22m to IPounds 16m. A number
of plants in Germany and Spain were operating short time.
However the Venezuelan business was a star performer, with profits up 16 per
cent from IPounds 10m to IPounds 11.6m. The group plans to expand and
modernise the San Felipe paper mill in Venezuela at a cost of Dollars 77m.
The directors declared a second interim dividend of 1.2306p per share for
the year ending January 31 1993. The board's intention is to recommend a
full-year dividend of 3.74p, an increase of 5.7 per cent over the previous
year.
