FT  30 SEP 92 / Sears to close 350 shops and shed 1,800 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SEARS, the UK retail and mail order group, will close 350 shops and shed up
to 1,800 jobs over three years in the latest reorganisation of the British
Shoe Corporation, which includes shops such as Dolcis, Saxone and Freeman
Hardy Willis.
The group also cut its interim dividend from 1.525p to 1p. Mr Geoffrey
Maitland Smith, chairman, said the final would also be reduced to give a
total of 3.5p, down from 5.355p. The cut came as no surprise to the market
and the share price gained 8p to close at 80p. It has risen 25 per cent
since last week's announcement of a withdrawal from men's wear.
The Pounds 32.2m exceptional cost of rationalising British Shoe pushed Sears
into a pre-tax loss of Pounds 8.8m in the six months to July 31, and
increased the loss per share from 0.3p to 0.5p. Turnover slipped to Pounds
902m from Pounds 923.7m, reflecting a Pounds 55.2m fall from discontinued
activities.
Pre-tax losses for the same period last year were Pounds 2.4m after Pounds
25.2m of rationalisation costs for men's wear. Mr Liam Strong, chief
executive since February, said the stream of exceptional charges was over.
The announcement of job-cutting at British Shoe follows a 2,000 reduction in
the workforce over the past year.
After converting some of the closed shops and opening others out-of-town,
the net effect would be to reduce the number of shops from 1,200 to to
1,000. The number of concessions (shops within shops) stays at about 570.
Freeman Hardy Willis and Curtess would be most affected. 'They sell shoes
cheaply to all the family,' said Mr Strong.
The footwear division recovered from a trading loss of Pounds 3.3m to a
profit of Pounds 1.9m on sales of Pounds 249.4m, down Pounds 7.7m. Dolcis
improved on last year's good figures and Saxone returned to like-for-like
sales growth.
Verdict Research, which monitors the retail sector, said British Shoe had
18.3 per cent of the UK's Pounds 3.73bn shoe market last year. The market
had been flat in real terms since 1986.
Other divisions contributed to Sears' Pounds 27.4m trading profit as
follows: speciality retailing - children's wear, women's wear and
leisurewear - up to Pounds 6.5m; Selfridges department store, up to Pounds
5.5m; home shopping, down to Pounds 11.9m; property up to Pounds 8.5m;
others, mainly discontinued, lost Pounds 6.9m.
