<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / Hershey may launch counter bid for Freia Marabou
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HERSHEY Foods, the big US chocolates producer, is considering a counter bid
for Freia Marabou, the Norwegian confectionery group which yesterday agreed
to a Dollars 1.5bn (Pounds 870m) takeover offer from the US Philip Morris
group.
Hershey is Freia Marabou's second biggest shareholder with an 18.6 per cent
stake, acquired in May this year for NKr1.16bn (Pounds 113.8m) from Orkla,
the Norwegian diversified foods group.
The Philip Morris bid has to be accepted by shareholders, who have been
called to an extraordinary general assembly on October 9. The offer has to
win two-thirds backing by Freia's shareholders to amend the company's
articles of association to allow the takeover.
Philip Morris also needs approval by Norway's energy and industry minister,
Mr Finn Kristensen, who said he will consider the sale on the basis of the
buyer's plans for the company.
Mr Richard Zimmerman, Hershey chief executive, said yesterday in Oslo that
his company last weekend made an unconditional offer to acquire Freia
Marabou for Dollars 1.3bn.
Mr Zimmerman said Hershey's bid still held but the company was considering
several options to gain control of Freia Marabou and has invited Orkla to
co-operate in a joint solution to acquire the company.
'We contacted Orkla on Monday indicating our intention to explore
opportunities to work together in the pursuit of Freia Marabou. They
expressed interest in continuing these discussions,' Mr Zimmerman said.
</TEXT>
