<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / The Lex Column: Jefferson Smurfit
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
UK institutions are traditionally wary of Irish companies, and have every
excuse to avoid them when they are barred from the Footsie. Even so, the
market can hardly deny that Jefferson Smurfit's balance sheet is in fine
fettle for a paper and packaging business at this stage in the cycle.
ItsIPounds 220m of net cash is in impressive contrast to the position of
most of its Scandinavian and Canadian competitors, whose debt in some cases
exceeds their turnover. Admittedly there is some Dollars 2.3bn of
off-balance sheet debt post the restructuring of JSC/CCA - but there is no
recourse to Smurfit, and there is value in this US joint venture which may
yet be cashed in.
The immediate challenge for Smurfit, though, is earnings, hit by the
familiar problems of overcapacity and keen pricing in US and European
markets. The company can only hope that its proposed linerboard increase
will stick, and that the pressures which have caused discounts of more than
30 per cent in North American newsprint really are starting to ease. But
while the stronger dollar should also make an impact on the UK and Spain in
the current half, profits are unlikely to be much more than IPounds 140m for
the year as a whole.
The shares, down another 11 per cent to 228p yesterday, have been
conspicuously weak since the end of March. Earnings will rebound sharply one
day, but the timing of recovery remains as elusive as ever. For the moment
investors are unlikely to be trampled in the rush.
</TEXT>
