<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It's an odd thing but during all the discussion of joy-riding over the past
year and more, never once have I heard any mention of young people elsewhere
in Europe engaging in joy-riding. So maybe it is a particularly British form
of flamboyant sexual display. Whatever the truth may be, joy-riding is a
favourite pastime in Belfast which provides the setting for tonight's
Screenplay on BBC2, You, Me and Marley (9.00).
The play won a small stack of awards for Belfast playwright Graham Reid at
this year's Edinburgh International Film Festival, so it promises to be well
worth watching.
BBC 1's Inside Story, The Assassin (9.30) describes the unusual career of
Michael Townley, a normal American guy until he married a quite
exceptionally forceful Chilean political activist. As a reward for their
anti-communist fervour, the couple were invited to join President Pinochet's
ruthless secret police, called DINA. Together they went on long foreign
holidays, taking with them a perfume-flask full of nerve-gas with which to
eliminate enemies of the state.
