<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / Big users' gas bills condemned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VERY large gas users face considerably higher prices than users in some
European countries and have not seen any price benefits from measures to
introduce competition into the UK gas market, Mr Ian Powe, director of the
Gas Consumers Council, said yesterday.
His comments will strengthen demands for lower energy prices from UK
industry, where many customers are already complaining about electricity
prices.
The Gas Consumers Council, which represents 18m British customers, said
yesterday one reason for the price rise for large users was the requirement
 -imposed by the Office of Fair Trading - that British Gas must halve its
share of the industrial supply market by the mid 1990s.
The release gas programme, whereby British Gas sells off tranches of its
contracted gas supplies to competitors, was inadequate, and the only way BG
could cut its market share was by putting up prices. That in turn did not
give an incentive to independent marketers to cut prices as much as they
might.
The GCC will shortly report to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission, which
is engaged in a comprehensive inquiry into the UK gas market.
British Gas said that in real terms UK industrial contract prices had
dropped by 30 per cent since the company was privatised in 1986. BG
accepted, though, that prices for large users were higher than in some
European countries.
In contrast, domestic gas customers paid less than in Italy, the Benelux
countries, France and Germany.
Mr Powe told a conference in Brussels there was 'a stark difference, to the
disadvantage of UK Limited, in prices paid in the big gas-consuming
countries of Europe and the UK at higher consumption levels'.
While household users have benefited from a tough price formula that has
produced two recent price cuts, unregulated industrial prices were creeping
up, he added.
</TEXT>
