FT  30 SEP 92 / Tory activists call for reform at headquarters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY party managers face the prospect of an embarrassingly high-profile
public debate on making Conservative Central Office, the party's
headquarters based in central London, democratically accountable to party
members.
Fifty local Tory associations are supporting a call for a special meeting of
the Tory central council, a gathering of senior party activists, to bring
about such changes. The group, spearheaded by the Party Reform Steering
Committee, a group of 11 activists, accuses Central Office of being 'remote
from the constituencies and out of touch'.
The difference between this and previous moves to reform Central Office is
that the party's rules say that its executive committee must summon a
special meeting of the central council if 50 associations require it. The
call is another headache for the national union, the voluntary wing of the
Tory which is already deep into arrangements for what promises to be a
difficult conference next week.
Central Office said the first step would be to check whether the rules were
as definite as the reform committee envisaged, and whether all 50 of the
local associations had indeed signed up to the move.
Sir Norman Fowler, the party chairman, has already promised a review of
spending.
Central Office is traditionally the scapegoat of the Conservative party
conference, with complaints about presentational failures coming from
representatives who are not prepared openly to criticise party policy.
Mr Michael Normington, the chairman of the steering committee, said
yesterday that the call for change was widely supported and that Central
Office had put pressure on many constituency associations not to join the
move.
If Central Office were properly subject to democratic accountability and
control by constituency associations, the committee argues, there would be
nothing like the level of dissatisfaction with it.
The committee is seeking the transfer of responsibility for Central Office
and party central funds from the appointed officers to a committee which is
mainly elected and then elects its officers.
</TEXT>
