<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / Sharp rise in company failures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS failures in the third quarter of this year rose by 53 per cent
compared with the corresponding period last year, according to figures
released today. They highlight the continuing sharp impact of the recession,
especially on smaller companies.
According to Dun &amp; Bradstreet, a business information company, the 46,545
failures in the first nine months of the year means the total figure for
1991 has almost been surpassed already.
In the third quarter, 15,823 businesses failed, compared with 10,371 in the
corresponding period last year. The total for the first nine months was 39
per cent up on the 33,532 recorded during the January-September period in
1991.
Last year saw 47,777 business failures, according to Dun &amp; Bradstreet. That
itself was the biggest number recorded by the company since it started
keeping the statistics in 1980.
Since the start of this year, on average, more than 1,220 businesses have
collapsed each week.
Of the total, two out of three have been bankruptcies of partnerships or
traders, indicating how small businesses have suffered worse in the
recession than big ones.
The rest of the failures have mainly been liquidations of relatively large
limited companies.
Dun &amp; Bradstreet says many small companies have been forced to go under
because of the chain reaction of cuts in orders from large companies and
'harsh competitive conditions' caused by high interest rates and large
company debts. It says the weak state of the economy seems likely to
'continue to devastate the small-business community' for some time.
The south-east, excluding London, has accounted for roughly a quarter of the
business failures so far this year. The total of 10,375 in the region
represents an increase of more than 50 per cent on the equivalent period
last year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
