FT  30 SEP 92 / Personal loans up as businesses repay debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES continued to repay debt in the three months to the end of August,
according to figures from the British Bankers' Association, which represents
the nine biggest UK commercial banks. The figures underline the weakness in
economic activity among businesses.
The repayments were offset by a rise of Pounds 2.7bn in borrowing by
individuals, mainly for house purchases, which the association thinks was
largely due to the rush to beat last month's deadline on the reintroduction
of stamp duty on all house sales.
In the three months to August 31, construction companies repaid Pounds 657m.
Other repayments came from hotel and catering groups (Pounds 410m) and
property companies (Pounds 274m).
Taking into account the activities of companies and consumers, total net
lending on a non-seasonally-adjusted basis during the three months grew
Pounds 2.3bn, as against Pounds 862m in the three months to the end of May.
Seasonally adjusted, the two figures are Pounds 2.9bn and Pounds 3.1bn
respectively.
