FT  30 SEP 92 / Falling pound prompts increase in gilt sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OVERSEAS financial instit-utions sold gilts worth Pounds 1.3bn last month as
they worried about the falling pound, the Bank of England said yesterday.
It was by far the largest monthly selling of gilts by non-UK institutions
since Britain joined the European exchange rate mechanism in October 1990.
It indicates that such groups may be averse to buying large stocks of
government bonds now the pound is floating outside the ERM.
Last month the government sold Pounds 1.2bn worth of gilts, taking into
account redemptions.
The state of corporate finances improved in the second quarter although
industrial and commercial companies continued to run a financial deficit.
Seasonally adjusted figures from the Central Statistical Office yesterday
showed a financial deficit of Pounds 2bn in the second quarter compared with
Pounds 4.3bn in the first. Gross trading profits of the corporate sector,
net of stock appreciation, were Pounds 20.5bn, more than Pounds 1bn higher
than the first quarter.
