<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / Sterling's decline helps oil industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FALL in the value of sterling after the UK's withdrawal from the
European exchange rate mechanism might add Pounds 2.5m a day to the output
of the UK oil industry, according to the Royal Bank of Scotland's monthly
oil index.
The recent rise in the dollar - the currency in which oil is traded - has
produced an 'almost complete about-turn' in the fortunes of the North Sea
oil industry, the bank's economists said.
In August, output rose by 2.6 per cent to just under 1.9m barrels a day, but
that was more than offset by a 3 per cent fall in oil prices to just under
Dollars 20 a barrel and a 1.2 per cent weakening of the dollar-sterling
exchange rate.
However, August's production at today's prices would have been worth Pounds
2.5m a day more - at Pounds 21.7m - leading the bank to have a very positive
view of likely output value in September and October.
The possible strengthening of international oil prices this winter might
increase output value even more. Many analysts are forecasting a tight oil
market, with an increase in demand.
The Organisation of Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed earlier this month
to freeze its output at its August level in the fourth quarter. Also, some
forecasters are predicting an unusually cold winter, which would also push
up oil prices.
The Royal Bank of Scotland said: 'The result will be a welcome fillip to UK
oil revenues - and particularly to those oil companies which have been
suffering earlier this year.'
</TEXT>
