<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / Call for shake-up of auditing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN SHOULD create an independent agency to appoint and oversee the work
of auditors of large companies, according to a study sponsored by the
Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales.
The report, by three academics, also called for auditors' responsibilities
to be extended beyond existing shareholders of companies, and for them to
detect material fraud.
The radical conclusions by Mr Christopher Humphrey and Mr Stuart Turley, of
Manchester University, and Mr Peter Moizer, of Leeds University, are likely
to prove embarrassing to the institute, which has argued strongly for the
retention of self-regulation through its own organisation.
The findings follow a detailed analysis of the 'expectations gap' - the
difference between the service non-auditors expect and which auditors
provide. The study says the gap has existed since at least the end of the
last century and auditors have tended to believe the fault lies with public
ignorance of their role.
The study argues there is an enduring expectation that auditors should
detect material fraud and that auditors should respond by accepting this
role, even though there would be an effect on fees charged.
It says that there should be an 'office for auditing' to oversee auditors of
companies, with appointments and the setting of fee levels taken out of the
hands of directors on whom they are reporting.
The study also suggest that auditors' responsibilties should extend beyond
existing shareholders to potential shareholders and existing and potential
creditors.
Mr Henry Gold, technical director at the institute, welcomed some of the
findings but said it was 'less confident' about the recommendations for an
'office for auditing' and to develop more explicit responsibility for fraud
detection.
He said the argument for independent regulation was not developed in
sufficient detail to analyse its effectiveness.
The Audit Expectations Gap in the UK. Research Board, ICAEW, PO Box 433,
Moorgate Place, London EC2P 2BJ. Pounds 10.
Observer, Page 21
</TEXT>
