<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / Australian balance improves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AUSTRALIA'S current account deficit narrowed significantly last month,
easing fears that interest rates would have to rise to head off a balance of
payments crisis.
The deficit fell to ADollars 903m (Pounds 380m) in August in seasonally
adjusted terms, from nearly ADollars 1.5bn in July. The unadjusted deficit
declined from ADollars 2bn to ADollars 1.1bn.
The government said the August figure was in line with its budget forecast
that the deficit would rise from ADollars 11.7bn last year to ADollars
15.7bn in the year to next June, equivalent to 4.1 per cent of forecast
gross domestic product.
'To all the Jeremiahs who were saying a month ago that imports are rising
inextricably again, I think all this proves that you can't put that much
store in one month's numbers,' said Mr Paul Keating, the prime minister.
Economists said the figures should end speculation that the Reserve Bank
would raise shortly official interest rates from 5.7 per cent to dampen
demand for imports.
However, the deficit is likely to widen over the remaining 10 months of the
fiscal year as a result of forecast imports of civil aircraft, liquefied
natural gas tankers and a recently launched telecommunications satellite.
In seasonally adjusted terms, most of the reduction in the deficit was
caused by an improvement in the trade account, which was in surplus by
ADollars 338m following a deficit of ADollars 104m in July.
Mr Chris Caton, chief economist at Bankers Trust, said the value of imports
had probably been inflated by a recent fall in the value of the Australian
dollar.
</TEXT>
