FT  30 SEP 92 / US group urges action on piracy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A COALITION representing 1,500 US companies yesterday called for action in
Latin America to combat the piracy of American movies, music and audio
recordings, computer software and books.
Appearing before a Senate judiciary sub-committee, Mr Eric Smith, executive
director of the International Intellectual Property alliance, released a
report detailing an estimated Dollars 660m in annual losses in Central and
South America.
The report estimated losses to US industry of Dollars 200m a year from
displaced sales through Paraguay's export of pirated audiotapes.
It claims that El Salvador is the Central American base of audio piracy with
a manufacturing capacity estimated at 100,000 units per month - nearly twice
the legitimate sales of the record industry in the Central American region.
The alliance released a second study concluding that the copyright-based US
industries are among the largest and fastest growing sectors of the national
economy.
