FT  30 SEP 92 / Nine killed as fighting flares in south Lebanon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LARA MARLOWE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIRUT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NINE people were killed in renewed fighting in southern Lebanon yesterday
including a 29-year-old Irish soldier with United Nations peacekeeping
forces.
Guerrillas from the Iranian-backed Shia Moslem Hizbollah militia launched a
rocket attack against a hilltop position manned by the South Lebanon Army
(SLA), Israel's proxy militia. Hizbollah, which recently won eight seats in
the Lebanese parliament, stepped up its attacks after the latest Middle East
peace talks closed in Washington last Friday.
Four Hizbollah and two SLA men were killed in the initial assault yesterday.
Later, Hizbollah guerrillas attempted to pass through a United Nations
Interim Force in Lebanon (Unifil) checkpoint manned by Irish soldiers. After
being denied passage, the guerrillas fired a rocket propelled grenade at the
guard house, killing Corporal Peter Ward. Two more Hizbollah gunmen were
killed in ensuing fire.
Cpl Ward was the 187th Unifil soldier to die in southern Lebanon since the
6,000-strong force was deployed in 1978.
