<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / Wheat war fuels Gatt dissent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS and DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE ESCALATING wheat export subsidies war between the US and the European
Community was condemned yesterday by trading partners in the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt).
Mr David Hawes, Australia's Gatt ambassador, said President George Bush's
recent announcement of an expanded subsidy programme would further squeeze
the markets available to 'fair-trading' wheat exporters.
These attacks on the US and the EC during the morning session of the Gatt's
ruling council provided an inauspicious setting for potentially acrimonious
exchanges expected later over the EC's refusal to bow to US demands for
binding arbitration on their longstanding oilseeds dispute.
Following two Gatt panel rulings in its favour, the US wants independent
arbitrators to settle the sum of the damages. It has threatened to impose
retaliatory tariffs for what it claims is Dollars 1bn in losses suffered by
US oilseeds producers due to market barriers in the EC. The EC has offered
compensation of Dollars 400m.
Both the oilseeds dispute and the tit-for-tat escalation of wheat dumping
could derail last ditch efforts to conclude the Uruguay Round of talks on
world trade liberalisation and plunge the US, the EC and their trading
partners into trade war.
Australia's call for urgent consultations to limit damage from the US-EC
conflict was backed by other rich and poor farm exporting nations in Gatt's
governing council. There were also renewed demands for an early completion
of the Uruguay Round of global trade talks, which would cut export and farm
subsidies.
Wheat export subsidies are one of the main outstanding issues blocking a
deal between the US and EC on farm trade reform which is needed to restart
the Uruguay Round negotiations.
Mr Rufus Yerxa, US ambassador to Gatt, said the US was pushing for a Uruguay
Round deal but, in its absence, could not allow the EC to go on squeezing US
world market share. Earlier, at a briefing, Mr Yerxa said the US share of
the Dollars 20bn a year world wheat market had fallen from 40 per cent to 30
per cent over the past 10 years while the EC share had risen from 15 to 22
per cent.
</TEXT>
