<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / North campaigns to keep aid status
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALL OF the 82 greenfield inward investment projects won by businesses in
north-east England and Cumbria since 1987 have settled in 'assisted areas',
a delegation from the regional regeneration body told Mr Tim Sainsbury,
industry minister, yesterday.
The body, the Northern Development Company, supports the case for the
region's 11 assisted areas to retain their status. It said the government's
regional industrial incentives were vital for the continuation of economic
regeneration in the north.
The development company said that the regional policy map, at present under
review by the government, should be extended to include parts of the
north-east coal areas that are facing more pit closures. It also said the
Copeland and Barrow districts of Cumbria should be included, having borne
the brunt of heavy job losses at the Sellafield nuclear waste reprocessing
site and VSEL, the builder of Trident submarines. Expected job losses in the
offshore industry, which employs 20,000 people regionally, should also be
considered, the company argued.
Today is the closing date for submissions to the government on its review,
which it has indicated is more likely to shrink than to expand the
assisted-areas map. The new map should be published early next year after
consultation with the European Commission.
The company's 15-page lobbying document presented to Mr Sainsbury says
assisted-area designation should respond to long-term structural
unemployment, not short-term trade cycle fluctuations - an allusion to areas
of southern England recently suffering from rising joblessness and now
competing for assisted-area status.
The NDC said the north region, covering north-east England and Cumbria, has
suffered from structural unemployment for 60 years. Since 1973 it has had
the highest regional unemployment rate in Britain, even though since early
1985 it has won Pounds 2.8bn of inward investment, creating or safeguarding
about 34,650 jobs.
Of the 82 new investments from overseas into the region between 1987 and
1991, 69 went to 'development areas' and 13 to the 'intermediate areas',
which receive less aid. Of all 202 projects in the region by overseas
companies in that period, including joint ventures, acquisitions and
expansions, all but nine were in assisted areas.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
