<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / International Company News: Restructuring at Sears, Roebuck
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SEARS, ROEBUCK, the world's second largest retailer, announced yesterday it
was spinning off or selling a large part of its successful financial
services operation in a large restructuring that should reduce corporate
debt. Analysts estimate the total effect of the restructuring will be to
reduce debt from Dollars 38bn to around Dollars 16.5bn.
The demerger is a big gamble for Sears, which is disposing of its most
profitable operations in the hope that, by reducing debt levels and
concentrating on a few businesses, it will be able to lay a secure
foundation for its loss-making domestic retailing operation.
The units Sears is selling accounted for 27 per cent of the Dollars 1.28bn
in group profits earned last year and 10 per cent of group revenues, which
totalled Dollars 57bn.
In recent years, this operation has lost market share to fast-growing
discount chains and speciality stores.
In the shake-up Sears intends to:
Sell 80 per cent of its Dean Witter Financial Services subsidiary (which
includes the highly profitable securities brokerage and Discover credit card
operations) to shareholders and float the remainder on the stock market via
an initial public offering (IPO) of stock;
Sell to private or public interests all of its Coldwell Banker Residential
Services group, which consists of the property brokerage and relocation
businesses, Sears Mortgage Corp and Sears Savings Bank;
Sell a 20 per cent stake in its Allstate composite insurance subsidiary to
the public in an IPO.
Sears expects the transactions to be completed by the end of next year, by
which time the group will be left to focus on two core businesses: its big
merchandise retailing operation, and its 80 per cent interest in Allstate.
Mr Edward Brennan, chairman of Sears, said yesterday although its financial
services businesses had been successful 'a thorough assessment of today's
economic and business climate led us to conclude that refocusing our
business strategy, changing our structure, and reducing leverage are all in
the best interests of our shareholders and Sears.'
The demerger will be seen as a victory for the large group of dissident
shareholders who, unhappy with Sears' poor earnings performance, put forward
a plan to spin-off the financial services business at the company's annual
general meeting in May.
News of the restructuring was well received on Wall Street, where Sears
shares climbed Dollars 3 3/8 to Dollars 44 3/4 in heavy trading on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
