<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / North campaigns to keep aid status
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALL OF the 82 greenfield inward investment projects won by businesses in
north-east England and Cumbria since 1987 have settled in 'assisted areas',
a delegation from the regional regeneration body told Mr Tim Sainsbury,
industry minister, yesterday.
The Northern Development Company supports the case for the region's 11
assisted areas to retain their status. It said the government's regional
industrial incentives were vital for the continuation of economic
regeneration in the north.
The company said that the regional policy map, which the government is
reviewing, should be extended to include parts of the north-east coal areas
that face more pit closures. It also said the Copeland and Barrow districts
of Cumbria should be included, having borne the brunt of heavy job losses at
the Sellafield nuclear waste reprocessing site and VSEL, the builder of
Trident submarines.
Expected job losses in the offshore industry, which employs 20,000 people in
the region, should also be considered, the company argued.
Today is the deadline for submissions on the government review, which it has
indicated is more likely to shrink than to expand the assisted-areas map.
The new map should be published early next year after consultation with the
European Commission.
The company's 15-page lobbying document presented to Mr Sainsbury says
assisted-area designation should respond to long-term structural
unemployment, not short-term fluctuations in the trade cycle.
</TEXT>
