<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / Move to avert liquidation at MMI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL-AUTHORITY policy-holders of Municipal Mutual, the stricken insurance
company, will press creditors to accept a scheme of arrangement if this
week's rescue talks with a number of European insurance companies break
down.
The Labour party yesterday said a scheme of arrangement would be 'the
preferable action for both local-authority and individual policyholders'.
In a scheme of arrangement - under Section 425 of the Companies Act - MMI
would cease to trade but continue to administer the payment of claims. That
would avert a potentially costly liquidation of the company.
Mr Stuart Bell, a Labour trade and industry spokesman, said such a solution
'is likely to produce better realisations from reinsurance debtors and would
permit earlier dividends to creditors than in the event of a court
winding-up'.
Mr Clive Grenyer, under-secretary of the Conservative-controlled Association
of County Councils, said a scheme would be 'the responsible course of
action'. It would allow local authorities to have at least some of their
outstanding claims paid.
The company yesterday called off a meeting with Mr Grenyer and other
representatives of local-authority associations, because of 'the delicate
nature of negotiations' with the French group, Garantie Mutuelle des
Foncionnaires.
Municipal Mutual insisted that its talks with the French group would take
place as planned this week. GMF said on Monday that it was no longer
interested in acquiring Municipal Mutual's business, but it is understood to
be prepared to act as go-between in MMI's talks with other members of
Eurosafe - a loose network of European companies that sell insurance to
civil servants and local government.
GMF's chairman Mr Jean-Luis Petriat is chairman of the Eurosafe consortium,
whose members also include HUK Coburg of Germany, Societe Mutuelle des
Administrations Publiques of Belgium, Gruppo MEIE Assicuriazioni of Italy,
Nueva Corporacion of Spain, Laederstandens Brandforsikring of Denmark,
Phoenix General Insurance of Greece, Lusitania of Portugal and Les
Assurances Mutuelles d'Europe of Luxembourg.
An increasing number of local authorities, especially those renewing in
October, are considering moving their policies away from Municipal Mutual.
Brokers say insurance cover is available in both the company and Lloyd's
markets, although buyers are generally having to accept much larger excesses
 -the portion of any claim which they must pay.
Some local authorities are reported to be finding difficulty in obtaining
insurance for employers and public liability.
The Consumers' Association pressed the government yesterday to issue a
definitive statement on the future of Municipal Mutual.
</TEXT>
