<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 92 / Northern Telecom blames recession for 426 jobs cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Belfast Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NORTHERN Telecom, the Canadian telecommunications company, yesterday
announced that it was cutting 426 jobs, most of them at its plant in
Northern Ireland.
The company blamed the recession for the redundancies and said the cuts
would reduce overheads and maintain efficiency.
The cuts involve 230 shopfloor posts and 90 managerial and administrative
jobs at the company's Monkstown plant in Newtownabbey.
The Monkstown factory originally belonged to STC, which Northern Telecom
took over two years ago. As a result of yesterday's announcement, the
factory will cease production of a range of products including point-of-sale
tills, power supply units and circuit boards for telephone exchanges.
A further 106 jobs are being lost at the company's plants in Basildon,
Essex, and in south Wales. The Basildon factory is being closed, with most
staff redeployed to nearby sites.
About 700 staff will continue to be employed at the Ulster factory making
high-technology transmission equipment.
The company said the redundancies would take place by the end of the year
and were designed to maintain the company's competitive position.
The workforce was informed at a mass meeting yesterday. A union spokesman
described the redundancies as devastating, in an area of Northern Ireland
already hard hit by redundancies.
Pirelli Cables, the UK subsidiary of the Italian cable and tyre group,
yesterday announced the shedding of nearly 300 jobs.
A total of 240 jobs are to go by the end of the year with the closure of its
copper cable factory at Bishopstoke, Hampshire. From next year, copper cable
production will be concentrated at the company's Newport plant in south
Wales.
Pirelli also said it would shed 50 workers at Newport in order to cut costs
and improve efficiency.
MMB stake taken, Page 29
</TEXT>
