<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (32): Europe, the universe,
and everything
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FREEMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PERHAPS IT was predictable: 1992 is the year of European integration, so you
can just imagine harried publishers scratching their heads a while back and
deciding to commission a series of Euro-business and language guides.
Essential information, where to stay, how to start a company . . .
Need to tell your Italian contact that you now use CD ROM storage for
financial records? Buy Essential Business Italian (Hodder &amp; Stoughton,
Pounds 4.99, 200 pages), turn to page 55 and the world's your ostrica. Or
your huitre, auster, ostra, should you wish to repeat such stilted phrases
in more than one language - the gurus at Hodder decided to repeat the
formula in Europe's main business languages.
Meanwhile at Cassell, an inadequate twist: should you wish, you can turn
instead to its Business Companions series. These glorified phrase books are
indeed 'new for the single European market'. At Pounds 12.99 a piece they
are also expensive.
The question publishers such as Hodder and Cassell should ask themselves is
who is going to buy such books. There cannot be many cross-border executives
who will learn very much from these guides. Perhaps the business travel
market has become more linguistically sophisticated, but in that case why
should anyone need help with such basic questions?
At least such books have limited pretensions. A companion series by Hodder
ambitiously suggests you can teach yourself Business German, a complete
course for beginners (Pounds 6.99, 218 pages), although it concedes that a
grammar might be a useful accompanying tool. That suggestion becomes
laughable when one opens Business Japanese, but perhaps the less said about
that the better.
Just as well, then, that Hodder has somewhat redeemed itself with Languages
in International Business: A Practical Guide (Pounds 10.99, 242 pages). The
editors adopt an appropriately serious tone and address sensible questions,
such as how can companies ensure that they have an organised approach to
language, defined as everything from staff training to promotional material.
This book does not set out to provide all the answers, but it does point to
the main pitfalls and as such is well worth the price for companies
venturing abroad for the first time.
That basic quality is central to the success of Working in France (Frank
Books, Pounds 8.99, 194 pages), where the emphasis is on how to find jobs
and even a career in the tricky French labour market. Advice covers
everything from graphology to where in Paris foreigners go to network.
Therein lies a warning for UK readers; the book has a US perspective which
at times is unhelpful. But in combination with Tim Green's useful and
amusing Real French; a thematic guide to fluency in speech and writing
(Harrap, Pounds 5.95, 127 pages), the aspiring citizen of Europe can get
down to some serious integration.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-230</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AE4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (34): Office bores
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JACKIE WULLSCHLAGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CHATTO BOOK OF OFFICE LIFE edited by Jeremy Lewis Chatto Pounds 14.99,
393 pages
WHY THIS anthology? The predictable are here - Wodehouse's Psmith in the
City, Sinclair Lewis' The Job, badly-aged 1970s horrors like The Death of
Reginald Perrin, all quoted so extensively that Jeremy Lewis has to
apologise: 'Repetition and familiarity are of the essence of office life'.
But this will not do for a selection that aims to entertain. Cumulatively,
it offers wry amusement of the self-disparagingly British kind, in the
reflections on national character, on our unchanging class-ridden and
irreverent attitudes to work. One-liners sometimes raise a smirk, but mostly
this choice is mediocre, unfunny.
Truly witty novels about work, like Scoop, are too sophisticated to retain
their sparkle in the slimline extracts allowed into an anthologer's
categories. Lloyd's most famous bank clerk was TS Eliot, and the best-loved
life insurance salesman was US poet Wallace Stevens, but neither dwelt on
the office out of hours. Kenneth Grahame, literature's most notable
Secretary of the Bank of England, and Charles Lamb, of the East India
Company, did; however, their hours were 10 till 4, and both wrote most of
their books at their office. Could they have done so now? And what of Kafka,
the world's most famous insurance clerk?
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-231</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AE3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (33): Business Ps and Qs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINICK COYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COMPLETE BOOK OF BUSINESS ETIQUETTE: THE ESSENTIAL GUIDE TO GETTING
AHEAD IN BUSINESS by Lynne Brennan and David Block Piatkus Books Pounds
8.99, 185 pages
IN THE American Wild West of the last century, you had to park your shooting
irons before entering a saloon; before gaining admission to the restaurant
in the London Ritz, the customer is nowadays invited to park his mobile
telephone. And I am told that the food is not too bad either.
This little gem of information comes my way from The Complete Book of
Business Etiquette, a compact guide of all the essentials needed to get on
in business.
For example, we are told that uncultivated behaviour at business meetings
exposes 'who is garrulous, but ill-informed; who is well-informed but a poor
communicator; who is dynamic but emotionally driven; who has integrity and
who may be treacherous.' Don't we all know someone in at least one of those
camps?
But do not gossip about them within the company, since that, too, is not
etiquette. It can also be downright harmful, since when gossip and rumour
are malicious and destructive, they can harm careers, business
relationships, even the company itself.
So, no malicious gossip, and no other contraventions of corporate or
individual business etiquette.
For example, no firm handshaking of Japanese businessmen, and certainly no
slapping on the back. Master the art of Japanese bowing - which is not too
easy, since there are said to be 26 combinations of depth and quality of
bows.
On the other hand, firm handshakes are very much the thing in the Arab
business world and, after a long period of acquaintance can even develop
into a warm embrace and kisses on the cheeks. But we warned: non-Arab women
must not be touched under any circumstances.
All in all, says the wide-ranging guide, good business etiquette is of
enormous importance in business today; it will help your company to win and
keep its customers and will also help to win promotion and personal success.
Not a bad promise for a practical book costing less than the strawberries
and cream at Wimbledon.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
