</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (29): Weekend papers have
the edge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHERE DOES the intelligent Briton in the street look for guidance about
money? The UK's specialist press is notably less powerful than the
corresponding publications in the US, where Barron's, Forbes, Money and a
variety of other periodicals command large circulations.
The main reason for the weakness of the financial magazine sector in Britain
is the unusually influential role of the weekend newspapers, both Saturday
and Sunday. Britain's uniquely strong and numerous national daily and Sunday
newspapers have blotted out various sectors which are powerful in other
countries, such as weekly newsmagazines, and they make life very tough in
the financial category too.
Exactly why the Saturday papers, in particular, should have been able to
seize the high ground of consumer financial advice is not clear, but at the
right season of the year and in a good phase of the market cycle the Daily
Telegraph on Saturday can carry anything up to a dozen pages on family
finance, packed with lucrative advertising.
Our own Weekend FT, of course, runs 'Finance and the Family' pages each
Saturday. The Daily Mail, however, prefers to run its Money Mail on a
Wednesday.
In the face of this competition the specialist magazines are forced into
niches. The Pounds 1.50 weekly Investors Chronicle (owned by the FT group)
has long focused upon private shareholders who want to keep track of the
companies they have invested in. Really enthusiastic amateur investors can
subscribe to a much newer monthly called Analyst, which at a thumping Pounds
240 for an annual subscription seeks to provide something close to a
personal advice service for private shareholders.
More specialist still are the numerous small circulation newsletters and
tip-sheets which reached their peak of prosperity back before the 1987 stock
market crash, when they could still boast in their advertising of how they
had picked Polly Peck at 8p and seen it climb to 800p. In much leaner times
the boastful ads have all but disappeared. The problem for the Penny Share
Guide and its like came to be that too many shares fell to a penny.
The mid-1980s also brought brief prosperity to the monthly finance magazines
such as Money (now Moneywise) and What Investment, the latter notable for
its extraordinary content of reply-paid coupons.
These publications cashed in on the unit trust boom but since 1987 have
found life much harder as money has shifted to building society accounts and
life and pension policies (which are aggressively sold through
intermediaries rather than advertised in the press).
But given a decent bull market the financial magazines could be packing the
newsagents' shelves once again.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-234</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AE0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (30): No room for glossies
in the UK - The failure of general business magazines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RHYS DAVID
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'FINANCE to fine art': that is what purchasers were promised at the
high-profile launch in 1986 of Business magazine. A gap - or so it was
thought - had been spotted for a high quality magazine dealing with business
issues and interests. And, with the Financial Times contributing its firm
grasp of what the business world wanted, and with the US group, Conde Nast,
offering its expertise in producing Vogue and other glossy magazines, it was
difficult to see how the project could fail, especially under the overall
control of minority shareholder Kevin Kelly, founder of one of the
publishing successes of the 1980s, World of Interiors.
Yet only five years later the two groups were forced to retire with heavy
losses, having failed to overturn one of the unwritten rules of UK
publishing - that a market does not exist for a successful, paid-for,
general business magazine.
The timing for the launch of Business could not have been more favourable.
In 1986 the stock market was still rising and unemployment falling. The
banks were falling over themselves to lend money for business start-ups, or
simply for personal consumption.
In keeping with the spirit of the times, Business set out to write about the
individuals who had become icons of the new boom age - not just successful
businessmen such as Lord Hanson, Sir John Harvey-Jones and Richard Branson,
but the likes of advertising enfant terrible Graham Fink, PR man
extraordinaire, Brian Basham, restaurant PR, Alan Crompton-Batt, and
designer Wally Olins. Others were similarly tempted by the apparent
opportunities. Eurobusiness, launched shortly after Business, was an attempt
to capitalise on the growing integration of European business.
During its existence, Business was not lacking in critical acclaim, or, for
most of the time, advertising. Prizes it won included 'Magazine of the Year'
and 'Business Magazine of the Year'. Its journalists also kept winning
awards. Until the bottom fell out of the advertising market in 1991, it also
managed to attract some of the most stylish advertising around, from
overseas banks, prestige carmakers, men's clothing manufacturers and other
advertisers anxious to present their wares in a high-quality environment.
Yet, in the words of its former chairman, Conde Nast's Daniel Salem,
Business was only a succes d'estime, and it never attracted readers in
sufficient numbers to keep going. Everybody seemed to love it, including
British Airways, which bought it for its Concorde, First and Club Class
cabins, and BMW, which advertised in every issue. Not enough people wanted
to buy it, however, to keep its advertising rate card moving forward in line
with inflation, or to bring in the extra advertisers that were still needed.
Circulation was held only with difficulty around the 45,000 to 50,000 mark,
in spite of a battery of subscriber incentives and tie-ups, including, late
in the day, a deal with the Association of MBAs which bought it for all its
members.
The contrast with comparable European countries is at first sight puzzling.
The German business magazine Capital sells more than 300,000 each month,
with Manager, a broadly similar magazine to Business, on 100,000-plus. In
most other European countries, too, there are strong business magazines. In
the US, where the success of business magazines was seen as a good portent
for a similar UK product, Forbes has a circulation above 700,000 and Fortune
is not far behind with more than 650,000, while even the very solid Harvard
Business Review has more than 200,000 purchasers every two months.
The problem in Britain, if it is one, has to be seen in terms of the quality
daily and Sunday press, and of the two main financial news magazines, the
Economist and Investors Chronicles, which between them clearly offer as
comprehensive a coverage of business as even the most avid business reader
is likely to require, and at better publishing intervals.
With a monthly publishing schedule Business, though it did get a number of
scoops, always felt it had to veer towards the offbeat. Really big financial
stories - such as the present UK sterling crisis - could not have been
touched because the magazine was always likely to be overtaken by events.
In other countries where there is a strong business magazine presence,
including Germany and the US, the press is more fragmented regionally,
making it much easier for nationalmagazines to position themselves at the
centre of business debates.
So, what options does this leave the would-be UK business magazine
entrepreneur, other than to invest elsewhere? In Britain the complement to a
strong national business press is a vibrant trade press, providing news,
views and features and, crucially, acting as the job search medium for
individuals working within the sector concerned. Because of its general
nature and monthly cycle, Business was never able to act as an information
board in this way
Even in the trade press, successful paid-for subscriber or newsstand
launches are now almost unheard-of. Most new entrants rely on the controlled
circulation route, and almost all those that are paid-for, such as The
Grocer, Caterer and Hotelkeeper and Estates Gazette have a long history and
deeply entrenched position to protect them against newer controlled
circulation rivals.
In the business field, the two surviving members of the triumvirate to which
Business used to belong, Management Today and The Director, both rely on
controlled circulation as their core readership - managers belonging to the
British Institute of Management in the one case and directors in the
Institute of Directors in the other. Both groups receive copies of their
respective magazines as part of their subscription.
Yet, the idea of a general UK business magazine keeps cropping up and it is
perhaps possible that a maverick operation might just work, as one
entrepreneur, Tom Rubython, seems determined to demonstrate. His first
venture into the general business magazine field was Management Week, an
irreverent mix of often none too flattering personality profiles, guru
potboilers, and 'management' news stories. It folded last year after not
many months' publication, but has now been reborn as Business Age, complete
with Business magazine's former slogan - Britain's best-selling business
magazine.
It may succeed, though the lessons of Business and Eurobusiness, and other
general titles such as Punch and The Listener, are not encouraging. In the
UK, unless there is a specialist category, or an area such as men's fashion
(which as GQ and Esquire spotted was not being covered in depth in the daily
press), newspapers rule.
Rhys David was publisher of Business magazine from 1988-1991.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-235</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AEZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (27): Work, death and other
problems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NO ONE EVER died from hard work, we reassure ourselves in those Western
countries which have adopted the Protestant work ethic. But the Japanese,
who should know, have a word for it: karoshi, meaning death by overwork.
Europe has not gone as far as the US in regarding a punishing work schedule
as a virility symbol rather than a sign that the company or the individual
is poorly organised. But the reverse of rising unemployment statistics is
increased pressure on those still in work. Awareness of the these pressures
has led to the growth of a consultancy industry aimed at tackling the
problems of managing time and stress. Courses and books on the subject now
abound.
Taken to absurd extremes they suggest a regime of obsessive note-taking to
establish work patterns and the implementation of artificial procedures to
reduce non-productive time. Taken sensibly they can throw a revealing light
on the disorganisation that lies beneath our apparently well-structured
lives.
Better Time Management (Jacqueline Atkinson, Thorsons, Pounds 5.99, 240
pages) begins with a series of questions. What sort of a problem do you
have? asks Ms Atkinson, a psychologist and an academic. Do you spend too
much time on trivial matters? Are you never able to finish one thing before
starting on something else? Are you unable to say No when asked to do
another job? Or do problems press in from the outside in the shape of too
many interruptions to your work routine?
You will not be able solve your time management problems overnight since
they probably reflect habits which have been ingrained over ten or 20 years,
says Ms Atkinson. But by analysing your present pattern of work and leisure
and making a conscious effort to plan your day you should be able to work to
greater effect and find more time for leisure pursuits.
Start by estimating how much time you spend each week at work, with family,
doing chores, following hobbies. Next keep a time log of how much time you
actually devote to these different activities. A detailed study of your
working day will probably show that a one-hour meeting took up to two hours
when you take into account the 'hidden time consumers.'
One sensible suggestion made in this practical and jargon-free guide is to
untangle realistic goals from daydreams. Many people dream of learning a
foreign language or mastering a musical instrument. But unless we make these
activities a real goal and fit them into our time schedules they become a
source of extra stress and frustration.
Time is Money: Save It (Lothar Seiwert, Kogan Page, Pounds 9.99, 222 pages)
covers much of the same ground, though the style is more academic. Diagrams
and mathematical symbols are used extensively to convey a somewhat spurious
precision.
Mr Seiwert, a time management consultant, suggests that you identify your
top five time-wasters from a 30-strong list which includes a failure to set
priorities, taking on too many tasks, lengthy meetings and procrastination.
When drawing up a timetable of activities set yourself specific goals - such
as reaching agreement on a particular issue - rather than just 'meeting with
so and so.'
Most work days have their productive periods, early in the morning or while
others are at lunch, and their less productive periods, so it makes sense to
time important tasks to take place in the most productive periods, Mr
Seiwert suggests.
Working Ourselves to Death (Diane Fassel, Thorsons, Pounds 6.99, 156 pages)
devotes more time to considering the causes of workaholism than it does to
suggesting a cure. This is less of a practical handbook than an apocalyptic
warning of what will happen if we fail to curb our over-emphasis on work.
Achieving a sound balance between the time we devote to work and to other
leisure activities is clearly an important one but Ms Fassel, a consultant
on work-related problems, spoils her case by exaggeration. 'Workaholics no
longer own their own lives,' she states. 'They are truly the walking dead.'
Ms Fassel's remedy for the disease involves limiting the time spent at work
or drawing up a work plan to restore balance. Companies may need to change
their systems if they demand too much of employees.
She borrows a programme of recovery from the techniques practiced by
Alcoholics Anonymous but rejects conventional time and stress management
techniques. These can become part of the problem, she argues, because they
create the illusion that the disease can be controlled and delay more
radical action.
One workaholic quoted by Ms Fassel went as far as pretending to join his
local golf club while using the time to make business calls. He was only
found out when his wife suspected he was having an affair. You may not have
let work take over your life to this extent but you might still benefit from
reviewing how you spend your time.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-236</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AEYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (28): Change for the sake of
success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PRABHU GUPTARA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CORPORATE TAKEOVERS AND PRODUCTIVITY by Frank LichtenbergThe MIT Press
Pounds 26.95
CULTURAL, STRUCTURAL AND STRATEGIC CHANGE IN MANAGEMENT BUYOUTS by Sebastian
Green and Dean F Berry Macmillan Pounds 45
ORGANISATIONAL CAPABILITY AND COMPETITIVE ADVANTAGE edited by Charles Harvey
and Geoffrey Jones Cass Pounds 24
IN SPITE OF the apparently diverse subjects suggested by the titles of these
books, corporate capability, productivity and change are their interlinked
themes, and all three books take a historical perspective.
Corporate Takeovers and Productivity revisits the question of whether
takeovers are worth the fuss. It examines the United States Census Bureau
and other data to investigate the effects of the explosive takeover activity
(in M&amp;As as well as LBOs) of the 1970s and 1980s on the productivity and
market share of manufacturing plants, on fixed investment and R&amp;D, on the
employment and wages of blue- as well as white-collar workers, and on
corporate diversification.
Lichtenberg finds that the least productive plants are the most likely to
change owners, that takeovers do not significantly reduce the employment and
wages of blue-collar and R&amp;D workers, but do significantly reduce the
employment and wages of white-collar workers; and that the effects of US
mergers and acquisitions are different from the effects of foreign mergers
and acquisitions, and different again from the effects of American LBOs.
Confirming Lichtenberg's findings, Green and Berry's Cultural, Structure and
Strategic Change in MBOs examines six case studies from different
industries, concluding that MBOs have succeeded as outstandingly as they
have principally because of the social, cultural, behavioural and strategic
changes which they were able to put in place. Most of the changes could
easily be implemented by any organisation which was so minded.
The puzzle, therefore, is not why MBOs did accomplish such changes, but why
do not the normal run of organisations manage it? Is it merely a question of
size, so that giantism defeats the best of its children, who need to be
liberated from its thrall in order to demonstrate what they can accomplish?
Berry and Green do not attempt to answer those questions. Organisational
Capability and Competitive Advantage does. And what a stunning collection of
essays it is, looking at managerial enterprises, marketing, industry
structure, the influence of the trademark on the rise of the modern
corporation, the relationship between corporate strategy and accounting
systems, the relationship between America's Graduate Business Schools and
American business, and regulatory responses to the market for corporate
control. The essays in this book help clarify and develop our understanding
of how firms and nations compete successfully or fail in an increasingly
competitive world.
If the message of the first two books is relatively simple and clear, the
message of the third is more difficult to summarise.
Though Porter's work has recently somewhat overshadowed Chandler's, his
concepts of organisational capability and Porter's concept of competitive
advantage are potent and valued tools in the analysis of modern business.
Chandler's conclusion regarding the British economy, which is described
elsewhere as 'the most unsuccessful advanced economy of the twentieth
century,' is that it is both short-termist and oriented toward financial
manipulation - and that this orientation has depleted the economic strength
of the country as well as of individual firms by directing attention away
from the underlying economic logic of corporate growth.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-237</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AEXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (26): Publishing - reading
between the lines / A look at mega-mergers and the Frankfurt Book Fair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOW FAR can the accelerating internationalisation of book marketing and
concentration of publishing go? Much farther, if the recent merger of the
UK-based Reed International with the Dutch publisher Elsevier, forming one
of the world's largest publishing and information groups, is anything to go
by.
The 1980's saw some mammoth publishing takeovers - Reed paying Pounds 540m
for Octopus, News Corporation Dollars 300m for Harper and Row, Hachette
Dollars 470m for Grolier, and Maxwell Communications Corporation the
(restrospectively outlandish) sum of Dollars 2.6bn for the US publisher
Macmillan - which, along with acquisitions in other media and advertising
areas, were more volcanic than fertile.
This year's Frankfurt book fair, is, according to some observers, likely to
be calmer than in previous years, reflecting the strains felt by consumer
book publishers everywhere. At the same time, its importance can only grow
as the European Community's single market becomes a reality and
transnational publishers generate more ways of selling a product across
frontiers. According to Paul Hamlyn, chairman of Octopus, part of the Reed
group: 'Book publishing will become more international and there will be
more hook-ups between America and Britain; we didn't do the Elsevier deal
because of books, but it helps.'
Of much greater, though less headline-grabbing significance, has been the
stealthy process by which English has become the international language for
educational, business and information publishers.
The Reed-Elsevier merger exemplifies the shift towards multinationalism via
the unifying factor of the English language. Although a Dutch company,
Elsevier has made itself a globally important English-language publisher
through its science publications. Its merger with Reed will smooth access to
other markets. The combined group would have revenues of Pounds 2.44bn and
pre-tax profits of Pounds 424m, based on forecasts for the year ending
December 31 1991.
Attempts to market books on a more global level are being made by other
publishers through means other than straightforward mergers. For example, an
international consortium of 16 publishers, led by Orion in the UK and Basic
Books in the US (a division of HarperCollins), announced at the start of
September a co-operative venture to publish scientific texts under a joint
imprint called Science Masters. The initial 12 texts will be simultaneously
marketed in more than 50 countries, initially in 16 large markets from the
autumn of 1994.
Within the EC, one issue which is currently on slow burn - though it may
heat up before the end of the century - concerns the levying of Value Added
Tax on books. Zero rating on books currently prevails in Ireland, Italy,
Norway, Portugal and the UK, but there is pressure to get those countries
into line with other EC members, most of which levy VAT at 6 per cent.
The global market for book publishing is still dominated by the US. While
the former Soviet republics and China are huge publishers, lack of reliable
statistics, political turmoil and absence of accurate means of financial
comparison means that the measure is still the US market.
According to a 1992 survey by Euromonitor, studying the performance of the
international book market in 1990, the US remains the largest book
publishing market, measured in terms of publishers' net sales, at Dollars
7.9bn (Pounds 4.46bn) annually, followed by Germany (Dollars 5.1bn), France
(Dollars 2.83bn), Italy (Dollars 2.81bn), the UK (Dollars 2.35bn) and Spain
(Dollars 2.15bn). But in terms of per capita annual spending on books, the
league table looks very different: Germany Dollars 64.79; Spain Dollars
55.74; France Dollars 50.32; Italy Dollars 48.86; UKDollars 41.40; and the
US Dollars 31.94.
In the US the recession has meant that publishers are being more cautious,
cutting the volume of new titles. According to Publishers Week, in 1990 the
number of titles published in the US fell by 27 per cent to 46,976, with
imported titles falling ever further, by 35 per cent. Particularly badly hit
were hardback and trade publications, falling from 53,446 in 1989 to 38,884
in 1990. Mass market paperbacks fared better, dropping from 3,722 titles in
1989 to 3,347 in 1990.
In value terms sales rose by 4.4 per cent in real terms over 1989, following
three years of real growth averaging 6.5 per cent. In the US consumer
expenditure on books and maps reached Dollars 12.5bn in 1990, up 3 per cent
in real terms but still less than 1 per cent of total consumer spending.
Euromonitor forecasts real growth in the US book publishing industry of 33
per cent by 1995, ahead of all other markets, with Germany (29 per cent) in
second place.
But there are still growth possibilities in children's books and in mystery
fiction, which almost 13 per cent of all adults purchased in 1990, making it
the best-selling category. The outlook for the immediate future in the US is
conditioned by at least one major demographic change; between now and 1995
some 3m school students will enter the market, which should encourage
educational specialist publishers.
In the UK the last decade has seen considerable growth. Publishers' revenues
more than doubled, from Pounds 907m in 1981 to Pounds 1.9bn in 1990, with
real annual growth of about 2.5 per cent. But 1991 was a very poor year for
the UK book trade; the number of books sold to the public - which account
for two-thirds of the Pounds 2.1bn overall UK market - fell by between 10
and 15 per cent on 1990. Euromonitor forecasts real growth in the UK market
of 5 per cent by 1995.
Publishers have been forced to cut costs by reducing the number of books
printed and publishing fewer new titles. Last year there were thousands of
job losses across the 18,000-strong industry, with 600 redundancies in one
month alone.
'It's a tough time for everybody and the US market is rougher than here.
There is a consumer resistance both in the US and the UK; the competition
for the leisure pound and dollar is getting greater. But it is an increasing
market; a lot of people do not buy books at all so the potential is there,'
says Paul Hamlyn.
In the UK the industry has polarised, between very large generalist
conglomerates and very small specialists, both in publishing and retailing.
Smaller publishing houses have been swallowed up by larger ones, so that of
the top ten UK publishers by turnover, only three - Macmillan, Oxford
University Press and Hodder &amp; Stoughton - are now not part of a large media
conglomerate. Specialist publishers of professional and educational books,
with more captive audiences, have done much better than publishers of
consumer books.
The dominant issue in UK book publishing is the future of the Net Book
Agreement, the mechanism which sets minimum prices for most books. A year
ago Dillons, the chain owned by the Pentos group, discounted the prices of a
range of books, following Reed's decision to publish its books outside the
NBA.
Were the NBA to disappear the multinationals could become more powerful,
able to exploit the competitive advantage of size. The NBA's abolition could
encourage book sellers to demand higher discounts from their suppliers'
publishers, thereby squeezing publishers' margins.
'I think the NBA is an absurdity now, only fit for dinosaurs. It should go
and people in the book industry should spend their time thinking about
selling more books. If the NBA disappeared book sales would increase by 10
to 25 per cent because they would be sold in places where the public is; in
the UK the public are not exposed to books now,' argues Hamlyn.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
