<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (2): A persuasive case for
US reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REVIVING THE AMERICAN DREAM by Alice M Rivlin The Brookings Institution
Dollars 15.95 190 pages
THERE IS no shortage of books and pamphlets arguing the case for US domestic
reforms. What makes Alice Rivlin's contribution unique and timely is her
focus on different levels of US government. She argues convincingly that
social and economic problems are likely to be solved only if far more
careful attention is paid to the division of responsibilities between
federal and state government.
The American dream of rapidly rising prosperity has faded primarily because
the growth of labour productivity has slowed sharply in the past two
decades. With output per worker no longer growing quickly, real wages and
the living standards of many families have stagnated.
Ms Rivlin, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution and a former
director of the Congressional Budget Office, argues that the federal
government should focus mainly on macroeconomic tasks. The most important is
to eliminate the huge budget deficits that absorb the greater part of the
savings of individuals and companies. Indeed, ideally the federal government
should generate regular surpluses. What Washington should not be asked to do
is oversee the microeconomic reforms that are so badly needed if workers are
to use capital more efficiently.
She argues that state governments - rather than distant bureaucrats in
Washington - should assume full responsibility for running programmes
designed to improve labour productivity. The 'productivity agenda' would
include the reform of education, the creation of new job training programmes
and the overhaul of crumbling infrastructure.
Ms Rivlin argues persuasively that such tasks are best entrusted to state
governments because they require 'bottom up' reforms and close attention to
local conditions. The skill training required in Louisiana, for example, may
differ sharply from that deemed appropriate in Maine or Montana.
Giving states responsibility for the crucial task of raising productivity
would allow Washington to devolve many of its responsibilities. It could
eliminate most of its programmes in education, housing, social services,
economic development and training. As a quid pro quo, says Ms Rivlin,
Washington should assume full responsibility for controlling health care
costs and guaranteeing access to care. At present, the soaring cost of
Medicaid, the joint state-federal health care scheme for poor families, is
putting state budgets under intense strain.
But even if states were able to escape financial responsibility for
escalating health care costs, the productivity agenda would represent an
intolerable burden.
Perhaps the most imaginative part of Ms Rivlin's plan is thus a radical
reform of state finances. She argues that the US has much to learn from
German federalism. In Germany, the central government collects most of the
taxes but shares much of the revenue with the Lander. For example, German
companies pay a value added tax whose proceeds are shared between the
federal government and the Lander, with disproportionate shares going to the
poorest regions. If similar shared taxes were introduced in the US, state
governments could be put on a permanently stable financial footing.
Starting in the 1930s, the role of the federal government expanded rapidly,
partly because state governments were frequently corrupt and inefficient. Ms
Rivlin points out that the quality of state government has improved sharply
since the 1960s: the most talented individuals and the most imaginative
reform plans are now often to be found in state capitals rather than
Washington. The time is thus ripe for a transfer of responsibilities back to
the states.
A redrawing of boundaries between state and federal government, Ms Rivlin
suggests, might help restore faith in government as well as enhance
productivity. People are cynical because modern presidents have repeatedly
promised action in spheres - such as education and industrial development -
where their ability to influence events is limited. If tasks were allocated
to the appropriate level of government, promises might be met and public
cynicism reduced.
As one of the more original contributions to the growing literature on US
domestic reform, Ms Rivlin's book deserves a wide readership. It is likely
to influence public policy whoever wins this year's presidential race.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
</DOC>
