<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (1): Behind the masks of
Murdoch - Raymond Snoddy welcomes a balanced biography of the driven media
mogul
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RUPERT MURDOCH: RINGMASTER OF THE INFORMATION CIRCUS by William
ShawcrossChatto &amp; Windus Pounds 18.99, 616 pages
TREACHEROUS ESTATE: THE PRESS AFTER FLEET STREET by Michael Leapman Hodder &amp;
Stoughton, Pounds 18.99, 304 pages
THERE ARE many Rupert Murdochs, some real, some mythical. There is Murdoch
the dark soul behind an Evil Empire, Murdoch the inspired businessman whose
destiny it is to be one of the most important princes in the global village,
and Murdoch the gambler who almost forfeited his empire through high-priced
acquisitions.
Then there is the Murdoch who can charm the birds out of the trees (before
trapping them), not to mention the man who can be both generous and mean,
who can show great loyalty and yet who dumped many of those who helped him.
A man with a romantic side but with little imagination and, for good
measure, a complex mixture of modesty, shyness and enormous ego.
There are already a number of books about this complex and driven character.
Some condemn him, some predict his imminent demise, some are simply cuttings
jobs. With Rupert Murdoch: Ringmaster of the Information Circus, William
Shawcross has written the best, fairest and most comprehensive account which
comes to terms, as far as anyone can, with the perennial question: What
Makes Rupert Run?
It will not please those who have come to throw stones. Shawcross does not
judge, although he provides ample evidence on which judgment can be made.
Murdoch may be 'an entrepreneur of genius' but broken promises, plunges down
market and cruel personal decisions have been carefully catalogued.
It can also only be described as the best Murdoch book so far. At 61, 'the
Dirty Digger' is only getting into his stride. After mastering newspapers
and television stations, Murdoch, controller of one of the world's largest
media empires, is now learning the nuts and bolts of running Twentieth
Century Fox film studios.
He is also looking forward to the day - perhaps 20 years off - when every
home has a single integrated box giving access to an entire world of
pictures and information. Murdoch wants to be part of that process, even if
it is as an 80-year-old non-executive chairman of The News Corporation.
But as Shawcross graphically tells, Murdoch scarcely made it beyond December
6 1990, when News Corp's Dollars 7.6bn (Pounds 4.3bn) debt crisis came to a
head through a small loan owed to a small bank in Pittsburgh, US. Murdoch
owed money to 146 banks and all had to be kept in the refinancing or the
package would fall apart. The Pittsburgh loan officer was not prepared to
roll over the loan, even if it meant the liquidation of News Corp.
After failing to get the bank's president even to accept his call, Rupert
Murdoch made the most important 'phone call of his life ('I had to beg', he
said). The bank official agreed to roll over the loan and Murdoch had
survived. As always, he was prepared to do what it took to do that.
Apart from being balanced and comprehensive, two things stand out about the
Shawcross book. One is the way he has firmly tied Murdoch the man to his
origins and family history. The other is the way in which Murdoch the
businessman is placed firmly in the context of the information revolution -
even if sometimes this degenerates into a list of inventions.
Murdoch knew how to exploit lax tax and offshore rules in Australia, and
could often find his way around media regulations. But he also knew what
computers and communications could make possible at Wapping and Sky, and he
was bold enough to carry it out.
Shawcross describes the two quite different grandfathers: Patrick Murdoch, a
stern piller of the Free Church of Scotland, and Rupert Greene, a
'roistering, charming, half-Irish gambler.' You do not have to be too
fanciful an amateur psychologist to see the influences. 'He is a
complicated, often ruthless, often charming, usually effective but sometimes
uncomfortable mix of Patrick Murdoch and Rupert Greene. He has more than one
personality. He can be prim and yet he is 'larriken', an Australian
troublemaker. He sees himself as a radical, he likes to provoke. But he has
not always been careful of the consequences,' argues Shawcross.
Throughout the book there is the leitmotif of pain suffered by people sacked
or discarded. People such as John D'Arcy, managing director of the Melbourne
Herald, summoned to London - he thought to be promoted - and then sacked in
20 minutes over a glass of whisky. Or, after 50 years of friendship, the
curt note to News Corp. chairman Richard Searby, asking him to resign.
How should the achievement of Rupert Murdoch be judged? Shawcross offers a
pertinent question, and an appeal, rather than a condemnation. Why should US
culture be imposed on the older cultures of Asia, the Middle East and
elsewhere in an era when a handful of people can touch the lives of
billions?
Not only is this power awesome, the responsibility also is immense. 'It is,'
says Shawcross 'a responsibility which Rupert Murdoch, grandson of the
Reverend Patrick, great-grandson of the Reverend James, scion of the men and
women from the dour beaches and strict kirks of Aberdeenshire, can
understand. He only has to grasp it.'
Michael Leapman, an earlier biographer (Rupert Murdoch - Barefaced Cheek)
has just published a more general book on the transformation of the British
press since its exodus from the boozy camaraderie of Fleet Street to more
sober high-technology premises.
Murdoch of course makes many guest appearances throughout, not just in the
context of Wapping but also in chapters entitled 'Hounding The Royals'? and
'Shame and Scandal'.
Leapman conveys well the changing feel of newspapers in the years since the
publication in 1957 of Dangerous Estate by Francis Williams. And in spite of
the ever-present controversies over invasion of privacy and reporting of
sexual scandals he is surely right to take an optimistic view of the changes
since the 1960s for both readers and journalists. 'We have more and better
writers producing more and better newspapers - and doing their livers a
favour into the bargain,' he says.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page I
</PAGE>
</DOC>
