<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / International Company News: ANI reports ADollars 66.6m loss
after Spedley group collapse claim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AUSTRALIAN National Industries (ANI), has reported a plunge into net losses
of ADollars 66.6m (USDollars 48.2m) for the 12 months to June, from net
profits of ADollars 77.5m a year earlier.
The figure included an abnormal loss of ADollars 76m, mostly relating to the
settlement of a ADollars 900m claim by the liquidator of the collapsed
Spedley group.
Mr Ted Harris, chairman, said ANI would pay ADollars 22m to the liquidator
following an out-of-court settlement. The group will also write off ADollars
28m in payments due from Spedley, raising the cost of the settlement to
ADollars 50m.
ANI also reported a tax bill of ADollars 81m, compared with ADollars 10m in
the previous year, after providing for the full cost of a dispute with the
Australian taxation office over the treatment of Spedley-related losses.
ANI, a heavy engineering and manufacturing group, owned 45 per cent of the
Spedley Securities finance group until 1989, when its holding was sold to Mr
Brian Yuill, Spedley's managing director. The group collapsed later the same
year.
Mr John Harkness, the Spedley liquidator, claimed ANI was partly responsible
for the collapse because of its failure to prevent alleged negligence and
dishonesty by Mr Yuill, who faces criminal charges in connection with the
collapse.
Mr Harris said ANI, which denied responsibility, had agreed to settle the
claim to bring an end to the uncertainty surrounding the group and the drain
on management time.
The settlement was within the range expected by the financial markets.
However, analysts were surprised by a reduction in the final dividend to 3.7
cents from 6 cents a year earlier, bringing the full-year payment to 9
cents, fully franked, down from 11.3 cents.
ANI said the reduced dividend related to economic weakness in Australia and
the UK. The group said there was no sign of a recovery in business activity
in Australia.
Sales fell to ADollars 1.16bn from ADollars 1.3bn. ANI's shares dropped by 4
cents to ADollars 1.71 on the Australian Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
