<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / National Savings cuts interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Savings yesterday announced significant cuts in the interest it
offers on fixed-rate savings products. The cuts varied between 0.75
percentage points and a full percentage point.
The Building Societies Association said it would ease pressure further on
building societies' mortgage rates.
The launch in July of the First Option Bond, which offers a fixed rate over
one year with tax paid, caused wide protest from building societies, which
said it was impossible to match. The initial rate for the bond of 10.34 per
cent gross prompted the Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester building society to raise
its mortgage rate, and this was followed by a cut in in the bond's gross
interest rate of 0.67 percentage points.
The gross interest on the bond has now been cut by a full percentage point
to 8.67 per cent. Similar cuts were made to National Savings' more
traditional products. The new 39th Issue Savings Certificates guarantee a
tax-free return of 6.75 per cent after five years; the 38th Issue paid 7.50
per cent. These certificates will now be sold in units of Pounds 100 rather
than units of Pounds 25, which should also lessen the pressure on building
societies.
Series E Capital Bonds, which offered 10 per cent gross, have been withdrawn
and replaced by Series F bonds which offer 9 per cent. The new Issue D of
Children's Bonus Bonds will also see a cut of one point, from 10.1 per cent
to 9.1 per cent.
Meanwhile, Halifax Building Society, the largest mortgage lender, yesterday
signalled that it is looking for high-value low-risk customers in the
housing market as it and Woolwich, the third largest building society, moved
their basic mortgage interest rates down to 9.99 per cent, David Barchard
writes.
In both cases, the reduced rates apply immediately to new customers and from
November 1 for existing borrowers.
Halifax's decision to trim its standard interest rate by 0.66 percentage
points to 9.99 per cent was a surprise as it means that many Halifax
mortgages are now slightly more expensive than those of Abbey National, its
main market rival, which last week cut its rate to 9.95 per cent.
However, Halifax has structured its charges to ensure that it undercuts
Abbey National for very large loans, if the borrower is seeking less than
three-quarters of the value of the property.
Halifax customers with mortgages over Pounds 100,000 will be charged 9.24
per cent, compared with 9.49 per cent for similar mortgages from Abbey
National. For customers with high loan-to-value mortgages, Halifax borrowers
will pay 9.70 per cent against 9.49 per cent from Abbey National.
</TEXT>
