FT  29 SEP 92 / N-dump plan will face long delay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PLANNING application for permission to build Britain's first underground
repository for radioactive waste is not now expected to be made before the
second half of this decade, Mr Michael Folger, managing director of UK
Nirex, said yesterday.
The slippage in the planning timetable for the proposed Pounds 2.5bn
repository at Sellafield in west Cumbria stems from the decision by Nirex,
the nuclear waste disposal company, to bring forward plans for an
underground research laboratory for the study of rock on the site.
When in July 1991 Nirex announced Sellafield as its preferred site for a
repository for intermediate and low-level nuclear waste, it expected to
apply for planning permission this year, with 2005 as the target date for
the facility to begin operating.
In June this year, after examining initial results from boreholes drilled in
the area, it announced a one-year delay in its timetable for the project
because knowledge of the site's hydrogeology was 'not sufficiently firm'.
Yesterday Mr Folger said that Nirex hoped the repository would become
operational in 2006 or 2007, but added: 'We are very conscious there's a lot
outside our control.'
Nirex will unveil details of the research laboratory proposal next month. It
hopes to seek planning permission for it no later than October 1993. Even if
granted without a public inquiry, it would take two to three years to
construct. Data would then need to be analysed before a final decision on
whether to seek permission for the repository.
</TEXT>
