<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / Anxiety mounts as poverty traps more victims: Fears over
possible cuts to the social security budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANTI-POVERTY campaigners are facing the coming tight public spending round
with at least as much anxiety as ministers.
In the most difficult public spending climate for years, there are mounting
fears that the Pounds 70bn social security budget - by far the biggest
single area of government expenditure - will not escape cost-containment
scrutiny.
Anti-poverty groups are rallying to the cause of Britain's low-income
families with a spate of reports designed to demonstrate that the poor
deserve greater support. The Low Pay Unit said yesterday that the pay gap is
wider now that at any time since official figures were first collected in
1886. In another report published today the Child Poverty Action Group
argues that some unemployed families have suffered cuts of more than 40 per
cent in the real value of unemployment benefit since 1979.
The latest official figures on poverty were published by the government just
before parliament rose for the summer recess. They give ammunition to those
who contend that the relative position of the poor declined during the
1980s.
Even so, suggests Professor Peter Townsend of Bristol University, one of
Britain's foremost academic specialists on poverty, the true position may be
worse. 'The government's procedures for gathering the figures are highly
technical and bizarre, and I have a fair amount of suspicion that they try
to choose data which put the poor in the best possible light.'
Poverty statistics are rarely open to value-free interpretation. There is as
much argument over definitions of poverty as there was this summer over
whether it causes urban disturbances such as those on the Hartcliffe Estate
in Bristol. The government's figures for 'households below average income'
show beyond reasonable doubt, however, that some of Britain's poorest people
became ever poorer in the 1980s.
Incomes of the poorest 10 per cent of the population after housing costs
were 6 per cent lower in 1988-89 than in 1979, while their share of total
income declined and the proportion of people living on less than half
average income rose from 9 per cent to 22 per cent after housing costs.
One of the government's intentions in its reform of social security in the
late 1980s was to target support on groups, such as families with children,
whom ministers believe are in most need.
Figures published in a written answer a few days before parliament rose show
the effect this policy is having on groups considered to have a lower
priority. The annual income support entitlement for a single unemployed
adult declined, at 1989 prices, from Pounds 1,725 in 1986-87 to Pounds 1,394
in 1989-90 - lower than in 1979-80, when it was Pounds 1,542.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, has emphasised that the
statistics for households below average income show a growth in ownership of
consumer durables among the poorest section of the population. Prof Townsend
dismisses this point as 'really rather absurd', saying changes in material
circumstances have occured throughout history and that definitions of
poverty must take this into account.
The issues which concern Prof Townsend and his colleagues at Bristol
university are debated with equal intensity at the Single Parent Action
Network in Eastville, a voluntary project in an inner-city district a few
miles away.
Poverty is not only a political or an academic issue here, it is a practical
one.
Maria, a single parent, brings up two daughters aged one and eight on social
security support of between Pounds 60 and Pounds 70 per week plus housing
benefit. She says she would prefer to work but that the high cost of
childcare makes this economically impossible.
Ms Sue Cohen, the project co-ordinator, says examples of single parents
going without proper nourishment to feed their children are not unusual.
Prof Townsend believes a mechanism to tackle 'extreme inequalities in the
wage structure' would have to form part of a successful attack on poverty.
He says: 'Politicians on all sides shrink from this, but the fact is that
pay developments have got out of social control. Extremes of inequality in
the wage structure have social outcomes which have enormous costs to the
quality of our lives. It is all very well trying to justify low pay and
unemployment as the necessary ingredients for competition, but I believe we
are losing some of the possibilities of being competitive by allowing
inequalities in the wage structure to become so extreme.'
Women at the Single Parent Action Network say an attack on poverty would
require strong, positive government policies to support the family -
recognising that families often contain only one parent. They regard the
government's plans to pursue absent fathers who fail to support their
families as a blind-alley approach which will increase pressures on some
mothers.
'Many women who come to the network display tremendous potential. But they
have little chance of realising it without adequate childcare and training
provision aimed at the particular needs of single parents,' says Ms Cohen.
'People very quickly get drawn into the culture of poverty. And the really
alarming thing is how quickly their children get drawn into it as well.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-290</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1ADCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / Teachers call for forcible opting out
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ALL SCHOOLS in each local education authority area in England and Wales
should be obliged to opt out of its control once 75 per cent of pupils are
at schools which have already opted out, the National Association of Head
Teachers said yesterday.
This would prevent a local authority from 'withering on the vine' to the
detriment of the diminishing number of schools left in its authority.
Mr John Patten, education secretary, welcomed the proposal. 'They are being
more radical than the government. I think it's quite a constructive input to
the debate and I will consider it carefully,' he said.
The government's white paper on education, published in July, says the
proposed Funding Agency for Schools will have joint responsibility for
school provision with local education authorities once the level of primary
or secondary pupils in opted-out schools reaches 10 per cent. The funding
agency would take over completely when the level rises to 75 per cent. The
funding agency would take over payment of funds to opted-out schools as well
as a range of powers from local education authorities.
The NAHT urged a rethink to stop the confusion of town halls and the funding
agency being forced to share power. It said that the agency should control
provision of places once a 50 per cent threshold was reached, with all
primary or secondary schools opting out automatically once 75 per cent of
pupils were grant-maintained.
Mr Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary of the National Association of
Schoolmasters/Union of Women Teachers, said the proposal was 'dangerous,
destructive and defeatist' and accused the NAHT of 'chucking in the towel
before the fight has begun'.
However, the NAHT yesterday attacked the white paper a free-market recipe
for 'confusion and uncertainty'. Plans for schools to opt for a new system
without local education authorities were 'fatally flawed', it said.
The suggestion that the cost of the new framework, including new
bureaucracies, could be met without extra cost showed a 'breathtaking
disregard of current underfunding', the NAHT said.
The National Union of Teachers, the largest teaching union, yesterday also
attacked the changes set out in the white paper, saying it was a 'charter
for political interference'.
It warned that the plan would take power away from town halls, which are
accountable to voters, and place it instead in the hands of the government
and bureaucrats.
Mr Doug McAvoy, general secretary, said: 'Instead of freeing children's
abilities through high-quality education, he (Mr Patten) intends to tie up
their future with red tape stretching back to Whitehall.'
Business should increase links with schools and make a 'blue-chip'
investment in well-educated young people, Mr Patten told a Confederation of
British Industry conference on the white paper.
He told the conference: 'We need to create an environment in the classroom
which actively promotes and encourages a positive attitude towards industry.
Industry can be exciting and rewarding. We must help young people to see
this.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-291</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1ADBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / Companies criticised over use of standard on leasing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES ARE failing to follow the spirit of the accounting standard
dealing with leasing, according to the latest edition of Company Reporting,
the Edinburgh-based monthly monitoring service of annual accounts.
'While most companies have complied with the standard, in some cases the
spirit of the standard has not been maintained,' says the October edition.
SAAP 21, the leasing standard introduced in 1984, allows certain leases to
be excluded from the balance sheets in companies' accounts.
These include 'operating leases' by which the company is not expected to be
exposed to the risks and rewards of ownership.
The standard has been criticised by bodies including the financial reporting
and auditing group of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and
Wales.
Company Reporting says many companies have found a number of ways of
structuring transactions to avoid placing leases on the balance sheet.
It says some companies have interpreted as a strict rule the guideline
suggesting that leases can be excluded if minimum lease payments amount to
90 per cent or more of the fair value of the asset.
An analysis of 280 published company accounts shows that 88 per cent of
companies show evidence of operating leases. If these were placed on balance
sheet, the gearing - or ratio of debt to equity - would increase sharply.
Company Reporting says the majority of companies with operating leases
satisfy the minimum disclosure requirements of the standard, and some go
beyond the minimum requirement.
All but 6 per cent of companies with operating leases disclose commitments
payable in the following year. Three per cent provide no analysis of lease
expiry dates for those payable in the following year, and 3 per cent offer
no disclosure of future commitments at all.
However, from a sample of 570 companies only 1.4 per cent disclose evidence
of having engaged in sale and leaseback transactions in the previous year.
A sale and leaseback occurs when the original owner of an asset sells it and
immediately leases it back. This allows companies to remove the assets from
the balance sheet.
Company Reporting, 68 Dundas Street, Edinburgh EH3 6QZ. Pounds 315 a year.
</TEXT>
