<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / Cost of work bullies counted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HARASSMENT at work makes poor economic sense for employers, according to the
Institute of Personnel Management, Lisa Wood writes.
Workers taunted over their sex, race, disability, union membership or even
age become inefficient and often leave their jobs, the institute said
yesterday. The institute is the main professional body for personnel
managers.
It has sent a booklet to its 50,000 members defining harassment and its
effects and outlining procedures to deal with bullying of all kinds.
The booklet says: 'Harassment exacts a high price for both the victim and
the employer because the stress, anxiety and fear it can impose on an
employee can cause absenteeism, illness and poor performance.
'Nor are the effects limited to the victim of harassment. Other employees
are affected to a greater or lesser degree. It all adds up to waste and
inefficiency as well as misery and it has to be stopped.'
Mr Roger Farrance, president of the institute, said: 'An environment in
which harassment occurs reflects as badly on the organisation as on any of
the employees within it.'
Harassment at Work. IPM, IPM House, Camp Road, London SW19 4UX. Free with
SAE.
