<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (8): A good read by any
measure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FREEMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVEN THE fanciest electronic calculator will jibe at the quirks of the
world's systems for measuring and quantifying. When is a billion a milliard?
What is a trillionth? The answers depend on where the questions are asked.
Thank goodness, then, for The Economist Desk Companion (Century
Business/Economist Books Pounds 20, 272 pages), which takes over from the
World Measurement Guide and goes a megametre forward. It gives an
authoritative description of the metric system, arguing that it will be
standard by the end of the present decade.
A series of chapters gives industry definitions and terms of everything from
shoe sizes to shotgun bores. The sections on weapons and space are
particularly fascinating. The danger of such information is that employees
will spend time reading the book rather than simply finding what they were
looking for. Managers should keep it locked in a desk drawer.
The last third of the book consists of conversion tables. There are even
tables for calculating mortgage payments and APR interest rates. All in all,
this is a thoroughly useful book and worth every penny.
</TEXT>
