<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (7): At last, the real
history of banking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FREEMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL BANKING 1870-1914 edited by Rondo Cameron and V I Bovykin
Oxford Pounds 68, 655 pages
BANKING IS an industry remarkable for its lack of history. Not in the sense
that the activity of banking has no history: Professor Rondo Cameron reminds
us that there were multinational banks as early as the 13th century. By the
time of the Medici bank 200 years later, financiers had discovered the
advantages of holding companies for controlling sprawling networks of
international branches.
Rather, the history is curiously unwritten, particularly in its later
stages. Banking, after all, has long been vital to and inseparable from the
trading impulses which move goods and services around the world. Yet we
remain largely ignorant of the way in which banks responded to a demand for
capital that became ever more international and intense after 1870.
As Professors Cameron and Bovykin point out, in the period to the outbreak
of World War One, international commerce grew at the unprecedented rate of
more than 3 per cent per annum for the world as a whole, and much faster
than that for the leading commercial nations.
International investment forged ahead in similar fashion. Britain was singly
responsible for 40 per cent of total foreign investment, but other western
European nations also provided huge credits to borrowers such as the US, the
Russian Empire, Latin America and Oceania. The market for capital became
more integrated and international than ever.
But what role did banks play in the process? And what were the reciprocal
effects of nations' progress towards industrialisation on the banks
themselves
In an impressive attempt to address these questions, Cameron and Bovykin
have orchestrated an army of scholars. They set out with the view that
international activity was crucial to an understanding of the mechanisms by
which banking structures in individual countries were formed into shapes
recognisable as the precursors of today's systems.
In 1870 Britain, for example, had the largest foreign investments and the
best developed banking system. However, UK domestic banks were scarcely
involved in international activity before 1890. Foreign investment was
handled mainly by the private banks, which exploited their extensive
overseas connections through the London Stock Exchange. Even when the
domestic banks did become involved, they tended to do so indirectly, placing
deposits at the disposal of bill brokers and discount houses for the
short-term financing of trade.
By contrast, Cameron suggests that in Europe there was a closer identity of
interests between the private and joint stock bankers, with the result that
the latter played a greater role in the mobilisation and deployment of
capital for foreign investment.
Obviously, however, there were considerable national differences and these
are usefully explored by the various contributors. So too is the way in
which the formation of national banking systems was influenced by the
experience and activities of the international lenders.
The single conclusion for which this volume will long be remembered concerns
banks and those other conduits of capital, the multinational corporations.
Contrary to their expectations, Cameron and Bovykin found that banks were
not responsible for the emergence of multinational industrial enterprises.
The banks certainly facilitated their expansion, mainly by providing
short-term working capital and by financing the international movement of
commodities. But their foreign investments were mostly undertaken in direct
transactions with governments or in the form of social overhead capital,
especially railways.
With minor exceptions, banks did not take the initiative in organising
trading concerns, nor did they control large volumes of equity capital. By
and large, industrial companies grew by self-investment.
Indeed, the final section of the book examines the rise of multinationals
across a series of industries, from oil to electrotechnologies, and gives
plenty of evidence for the bankers' reticence. One proposed chapter on the
chemical industry was abandoned when the author showed that there was simply
too little bank involvement to be of interest.
Cameron posits a straightforward explanation. In both its private and joint
stock forms, international banking had already developed into a highly
specialised business. Its leaders recognised their risk-taking as quite
distinct from that of industrial entrepreneurs, and where they paid too
little heed to that central observation, they usually regretted it.
By any standard, Cameron and Bovykin have put together an important volume.
In the impoverished context of banking history, the book stands out as a key
work which will form the basis of much future study.
If there is a criticism, it is that the project has been too long in the
making - it was conceived a decade ago, when it was remarkable for its
cooperation between then Soviet and western historians. Inevitably, that
seems less extraordinary today. Although there is a neat circularity about
descriptions of bankers to the Russian empire, the reader cannot help
noticing ideological confusion among some contributors which obscures
important questions.
There is, for example, an unhelpful debate on the connection between
international banking and capitalist imperialism. It is a relief when
Cameron dispatches the subject in a telling but diplomatic conclusion.
Britain, which had both the largest empire and the most money to lend, made
more than half of its foreign investments in independent countries.
As for France, less than 10 per cent of its investments went to French
colonies. The notion of a systematic connection between foreign investment
and imperialism fails the simplest examination.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-296</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AC6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (6): A primer for Eastern
Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LINDA BILMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EAST EUROPEAN OPPORTUNITY by Marvin Zonis and Dwight Semle John Wiley
Dollars 49.95, 438 pages
ANYONE DOING business in Eastern Europe knows that accurate statistics are
hard to find. Sources, even good ones, quickly turn obsolete. Here, hot off
the press, is a new, thick resource book by Professor Marvin Zonis and Mr
Dwight Semler of the University of Chicago, which should help fill the void
for this season, at least.
The East European Opportunity is a compendium of facts (historical,
demographic, economic, cultural, legislative) for each Eastern European
country: Czechoslovakia, Romania, Bulgaria, Hungary, Poland, Yugoslavia.
The book's main strength is that if provides detailed statistics for
countries like Bulgaria and Romania, where very little information exists.
For example, in Bulgaria, 30 per cent of households own vacuum cleaners;
installed electricity-generating capacity is 11.31m. kilowatts. The main
weakness of the book is that, alas, the section on Yugoslavia is a painful
reminder of what that country used to be.
The authors have written something akin to Fodor's Europe - a general guide
to the region with 60 to 70 pages devoted to each country.
Anyone who is working in one of the countries would require far more
detailed information, of the sort published in weekly newsletters and
textline updates. But as a primer, and a factual sourcebook for the region,
this must be one of the best new volumes on the market.
</TEXT>
