<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (5): Earth first - and
humans second
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WAY: AN ECOLOGICAL WORLD VIEW by Edward Goldsmith Rider Pounds 12.99,
442 pages
NATURE'S WEBB: AN EXPLORATION OFECOLOGICAL THINKING by Peter Marshall Simon
&amp; Schuster Pounds 9.99, 502 pages
HOW MUCH IS ENOUGH? by Alan Durning Earthscan Pounds 8.95, 128 pages
TEDDY GOLDSMITH'S book is readable only if you share certain beliefs with
him. First, that 'if current trends persist, the planet will cease to be
capable of supporting complex forms of life'. Second, that science, economic
growth and individualism are undesirable. Third, that these messages are so
important that they justify considerable repetition.
Goldsmith, brother of financier James, has found inspiration in the 'Gaia'
philosophies of the maverick British scientist James Lovelock. According to
Gaia, the planet and its oceans, rocks and life, form a unifed system which
regulates the conditions that sustain life. Goldsmith maintains that 'there
is thus a single law which governs the behaviour of the whole cosmic
hierarchy'. He adds 'our modern society has quite clearly set out
systematically to deviate from the Way' - the path that allows this
stability.
Goldsmith's 66 chapters, which assert principles such as 'Ecology seeks to
establish the laws of nature' and 'Gaia is alive', by the end become
claustrophobic, defining his philosophy by the things he rejects. He is
contemptuous of birth control as an aid to the population problems of the
Third World. He dismisses the use of medicine to cure 'individual sufferers'
because 'it will always serve the interests of industrialists and their
political allies (through pharmaceutical profits) but it will do nothing to
reduce the incidence of the disease', which is a symptom of the world's
divergence from the Way. This shows little regard for people and less for
accuracy - what about smallpox?
Peter Marshall also finds a solution to the world's problems in Gaia. A
broad though shallow survey of ecological thinking, his book is full of
ill-expressed aphorisms such as 'The Indians went down with the the buffalo.
Ecocide was followed by genocide.' His technique is to award points to the
world's religions, poets, philosophers and scientists for ecological
soundness. Thus he compliments Plato for 'anticipating Gaia' in describing
the world as a 'living being', but criticises Benedictine monks for
dominating nature by 'stealing' honey from bees.
When he turns to musing on Gaia he becomes tangled in its incoherence: how
to describe a system that regulates its 'organs' to sustain life without
personifying the planet - a vocabulary to which he eventually surrenders. He
concludes with relief that something bigger than mere humans is looking
after the planet's fate and that 'Gaia offers almost a new pagan religion in
a secular age'.
Guilt as well as fear appears to be the impulse behind How Much is Enough?,
one of a series from the environmentally-pessimistic Worldwatch Institute in
Washington. Like Goldsmith, Alan Durning believes that economic growth is
undesirable, and he is similarly trying to find 'a path of development that
does not lead to ruin'.
He blames advertising, commercial television and shopping malls for creating
'needs' in people where none existed. He sees the growth of material desire
as the corruption of morality: 'Sadly, hard-pressed developing nations sell
their ecological souls all too often in the attempt to make ends meet'.
Material goods, beyond a basic level, do not make people happy and their
production damages the environment.
These propositions can be contested, as can his pessimism. He does not
distinguish between growth and the environmental damage it produces, which
can often be reduced by forethought or regulation, so he has no prescription
for reducing that damage except reducing growth. Mistrustful of science, he
does not believe it can offer solutions to the expanding population and - as
he sees it - fast vanishing resources of the planet. But the past few
decades have multiplied the yield of many cereals, and estimates of the
planet's reserves of oil and gas have risen eightfold in the past 40 years.
Without justifying the reasons for pessimism more solidly, the book seems
puritanical in its equation of material desire with guilt. These authors
share a longing for a simpler, more spiritual or more innocent life. They
are dismissive of other people's desires, which include material goods, and
of the ingenuity that people devote to achieving them.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-298</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AC4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (4): Why banks must beware
securities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIT MCMAHON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL BANKING DEREGULATION: THE GREAT BANKING EXPERIMENTby Richard
Dale Blackwell Pounds 40, 211 pages
SHOULD BANKS be allowed to get into the securities business? To some the
question may seem absurd. No one asks whether a tobacco company should be
allowed to diversify into, say, food processing. The only relevant question
is whether experience and analysis suggest that such a move would be in the
long term interest of the company and its shareholders.
Banks, however, are special. Failure, or the threat of failure of one bank,
can weaken rather than strengthen its competitors. Because of their central
position in the financial economy, what happens to banks can have serious
knock-on effects. So banks are regulated in a way other industries are not.
On mixing banking and securities businesses, regulatory and institutional
practice has varied widely. In Germany and Switzerland it has always been
allowed. In the UK it has only prevailed since 'Big Bang' in 1986. In the US
it was common in the 1920s but has been illegal under the Glass-Steagall Act
since 1933 because it was thought to have contributed to the Great
Depression. In Japan, a law analogous to Glass-Steagall has been in force
since the war under a US legal code.
Richard Dale's study is a model of clarity in exposition and fair-mindedness
in argument. The central chapters describe the position in half-a-dozen
countries, analysing the underlying dynamics: how and why did matters come
to be as they are and what are the pressures for change?
Framing these chapters is an excellent discussion of the arguments in
principle for and against the merging of banking and securities activities.
Banks have usually argued in favour, citing potential economic benefits for
themselves and their customers in terms of greater competition, cost savings
and the convenience of 'one-stop' banking. Dale is prepared to accept the
force of these arguments (though experience in London since Big Bang might
argue for scepticism).
Regulators and legislators tend to have been cautious on two main grounds:
potential conflicts of interest and the dangers of contagious risk.
Conflicts of interest can arise when the roles of principal and agent or
adviser are combined - the possibilities of 'stuffing' clients with
particular securities; of all kinds of insider information; and of
distortion of securities markets by the lending power of banks. Again,
however, Dale is not too worried by these problems believing, perhaps
reasonably, that a regime of Chinese Walls, properly policed and legally
enforced, will minimise the dangers.
Dale's over-riding concern is with increased risk. Although later work
appears to absolve universal banking in the US in the 1920s from most of the
blame for exacerbating the Depression, and although securities activities do
not appear statistically more risky than banking, there remains for Dale the
crucial point that 'they do provide opportunities for additional risk-taking
for aggressively managed institutions'. The behaviour of the US Savings and
Loan institutions provides him with an awful warning.
If a bank is allowed to do securities business, how can we avoid the danger
that losses in that business may threaten the individual bank and thus -
potentially - the system? First, we need adequate supervision. But the
securities industry needs its own regulators. So a conglomerate bank will
have at least two (often more) supervisors, with attendant dangers of
divided responsibilities. Dale is critical of the UK's pragmatic solution to
the problem by means of establishing for each institution a lead-regulator
with arrangements for passing information between regulators. It is untidy,
but probably works better in practice than Dale allows.
But not even a perfect supervisory regime can (or should) prevent losses.
If, in spite of all efforts, a securities subsidiary of a bank runs up
losses that are substantial in relation to the bank's balance sheet, how is
the bank to be protected?
One solution, canvassed in the US in the current debate on whether to repeal
Glass-Steagall, is to make it legally possible (or even required) for the
parent to walk away from the subsidiary. Dale argues forcibly (and surely
rightly) that this would in practice prove impossible, or dangerous - or
both.
The opposite solution is, while accepting that the parent must take
responsibility, to require that the subsidiary is fully, separately
capitalised. But, Dale argues, to be effective this approach is likely to
make it economically pointless for the two activities to be combined.
So Dale believes the circle cannot be squared. In this, he is perhaps too
tidy-minded. But he is right to warn of the risks of experimentation,
especially in the present state of the world's financial system - risks of
which those in Brussels charged with developing the prospective regime for
the EC appear to under-rate.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-299</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AC3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / London Stock Exchange: Analysts strike at ICI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO, STEVE THOMPSON and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SAVAGE downgrade and sell recommendation on ICI shares by Hoare Govett,
joint broker to the blue chip chemical group, sent the stock tumbling and
had other brokers reaching for their red pens. The company appeared to have
hinted at a poor third quarter's trading.
BZW, ICI's other broker, and Goldman Sachs revised forecasts down to Pounds
660m, and James Capel to Pounds 650m. Other houses are expected to follow
suit today. The downgrades raised questions over whether ICI would maintain
its dividend, which on Hoare's figures would barely be covered.
Hoare cut its 1992 profit forecast by 21 per cent to Pounds 620m - with
1993's forecast reduced from Pounds 1bn to Pounds 875m. It also moved from a
hold to an overvalued stance, and analyst Mr Martin Evans believes that the
shares are some 10 per cent overvalued. Yesterday's fall left the shares
down 63 at 1145p.
ICI was believed to have told analysts that third quarter trading had been
'bleak', with European bulk chemicals business particularly badly hit and US
trading not helped by weakness in the dollar.
Drug stocks ease
Pharmaceutical stocks remained under pressure as US buyers continued to
respond to 'take profits' advice amid worries about a Democratic party win
in the US presidential elections. Not even positive trading news for two
stocks could reverse the downward trend. Glaxo, still suffering from its
comparison with US drugs group Merck, revealed good news for one of its
leading products in France, but closed 24 off at 746p. Wellcome, which
received US approval for one of its second line products, retreated 41 to
909p. The company was also endorsed by Merrill Lynch yesterday as 'the best
UK drug stock', despite a small downgrading by the US-owned broker.
Taking a different tack yesterday, Mr Andy Porter, drugs specialist at
Nikko, advised clients to take advantage of a 'classic UK buying
opportunity' in the drugs sector. Mr Porter argued that the current US
selling is prompted by currency worries and that the US political concerns
are already in the price. He said that when the currency situation
stabilised, UK drug stocks would need to be upgraded by around 10 per cent.
Cable &amp; Wireless (C &amp; W) remained in the firing line as worries about
increased competition in international traffic were followed by a report
that talks aimed at forging a link between C &amp; W and US West, the US
telecoms group, had been terminated.
C &amp; W shares have been very active this year as the market has reacted to
reports of imminent links with either AT&amp;T or US West.
Analysts said the market had overreacted. 'The merest hint of a shift in
strategy by C &amp; W will get the shares on the move; what the market needs to
remember is that C &amp; W is a strong, well-managed global company with a
rapidly expanding earnings profile.' C &amp; W shares opened sharply lower at
555p but quickly rallied to close only 9 off at 573p after turnover of 3.2m.
Utilities responded to a series of recent brokers circulars suggesting that
the water and electricity sectors had been oversold since the withdrawal
from the ERM, a move that triggered an upsurge in interest-rate sensitive
and cyclical stocks.
London Electricity rose 7 to 390p, while Wessex outperformed the water
sector, closing 20 higher at 510p.
Very large turnover in Guinness followed French group LVMH (Moet Hennessy
Louis Vuitton) increasing its stake in the drinks company to 24 per as part
of a complex cross-share agreement between the two.
Yesterday's share purchase was caused by the take-up by Guinness in June of
a batch of conversion shares which reduced LVMH's holding slightly below the
agreed level. SG Warburg bought 11m Guinness shares at 555p for the French
group in a move which had been anticipated for some weeks and had helped to
maintain Guinness's share price.
It is thought the French group was waiting for some stability in the
currency markets before making its purchase. Guinness shares closed at 540p,
off 12. Turnover reached 26m.
Banks shares stumbled after recently outperforming the market, upset both by
press comment suggesting the sector had been overbought and also by hints of
profit downgrades.
TSB, still burdened by market worries over the performance of its Hill
Samuel merchant bank, drifted back 4 to 132p although turnover was an
unremarkable 2.2m. Barclays drifted off 12 to 362p and Lloyds 14 to 452p.
HSBC fell 55 to 406p on 6.2m.
Currency factors helped to lift Unilever, as dealers reported fund managers
switching out of the Dutch NV and into the UK plc on a belief that that
funds would benefit from faster earnings growth in sterling. The food group
was also benefiting from talk in some quarters that it was relatively cheap.
The shares rose 13 to 1062p.
Among brewery stocks, Grand Met slipped 26 to 423p after a large line of
stock overhung the market and BZW downgraded the group; just before the
close a block of 2m shares changed hands at 423p.
In a weak stores sector, Boots suffered along with the other drugs stocks,
the shares retreating 14 to 483p. Kingfisher lost 20 to 515p as fears of a
price war in the DIY business reappeared and the chairman was reported to
have warned that prices may have to rise in the whole group as a result of
sterling devaluation. Ladbroke also fell on DIY worries, the shares down 13
1/2 at 160 1/2 p. Pentos declined 6 to 77 after SG Warburg was said to have
crossed a block of 6.2m shares at 75p. Turnover reached 12.7m.
Kenwood Appliances, the electrical goods manufacturer, slumped 42 to 245p.
Albert E Sharp, the stockbroker, visited the group and was said to have
joined other broking houses in shifting its current year profits forecast to
below Pounds 10m.
Holders of British Aerospace continued to sell the stock at every
opportunity in the wake of last week's disappointing figures. The shares
fell a further 9 to 116p in heavy trade of 5.9m. The company has invited
analysts to a presentation this morning for what one observer called 'an
attempt to steady nerves'. Suggestions that BAe could receive a bid offer
from cash rich GEC, 3 up at 248p, continued to circulate.
Shares in motor components group T and N were heavily traded and volume rose
to 11m, mainly due to one trade of 5.9m. Part of that block continued to
overhang the market and the shares gave up 5 to 147p.
