<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The Labour Party at Blackpool: Maastricht rebels fail to
dent leadership's resolve
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GRASSROOTS rebellion in favour of a national referendum on the Maastricht
treaty was halted in its tracks yesterday when Mr Gerald Kaufman was joined
by senior trade union leaders to argue against a plebiscite.
The outcome was an overwhelming vote against two motions - one which opposed
ratification of the treaty, the other which pressed for a referendum.
Senior party officials pointed out that the defeat for the opponents of
Maastricht was not merely due to the union barons, but also sprang from
overwhelming support for the leadership from constituency parties.
They pointed out also that the show-of-hands vote so clearly backed the
platform that the rebels waived their right to demand a card vote which
would have shown the exact scale of their defeat.
As a result, Mr John Smith, the party leader, can expect to see his hand
substantially strengthened when he presents his tactics to the members of
his parliamentary party, many of whom are clearly more critical than the
conference of his stance.
In his speech, Mr Kaufman, who stepped down this summer as shadow foreign
secretary, warned that a referendum would help the Conservatives out of
their difficulties on Europe and threatened to split Labour.
He urged the party to campaign for greater powers for the European
Parliament, greater EC aid for the regions and use of the EC as a 'force to
redress Tory domestic policy'.
He said the Community was far from perfect but Labour had much to gain from
'getting the best possible out of the EC'.
The centrepiece of the government's Europe policy had become a vacuum, he
said.
'Maastricht is the Tories' problem,' Mr Kaufman said. 'We should not turn it
into Labour's problem.'
A referendum would 'create unnecessary divisions in the Labour party, in
every union, in every branch, in every constituency Labour party, in the
parliamentary Labour party,' he said.
Similar views were advanced by Mr Gavin Laird, the engineers' and
electricians' leader, and Mr Alan Tuffin of the communications workers.
For the rebels, Mr Tony Benn, the former cabinet minister and veteran
leftwing MP for Chesterfield, argued forcefully that it was wrong that
Labour should oppose a democratic vote on the Maastricht treaty when the
French and Danes had held referendums.
He added: 'We pride ourselves on one member, one vote to elect the leader
(of the party) but not one member, one vote to decide the future of this
country.'
But in spite of a warm reception, the conference voted overwhelmingly
against him.
</TEXT>
