<DOCNO>FT923-343</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1ABUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The Labour Party at Blackpool: Election post-mortem kept
short - Delegates want to avoid dwelling on the defeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LABOUR conference's post-mortem on the election took less than an hour
yesterday, squeezed between a European policy debate and the drama of
National Executive Committee election results.
Some delegates might have preferred it not to have taken place at all.
The media, voters' distrust, a lack of appeal to women, misleading opinion
polls, and campaign strategy mistakes were identified as the main culprits
for what Mr Larry Whitty, party secretary, admitted had been 'a crushing
disappointment from which we have yet to recover'.
But conference delegates appeared unwilling even to discuss whether a fourth
successive election defeat justified a more wide-ranging re-think.
The shadow Budget or links with trade unions did not figure. The shadow
communications agency - hated by the Labour left - was only mentioned
obliquely. The only decision was to instigate a study of attitudes of women
voters.
'The feeling is that the tide has come in and gone out again; it (the
election result) is no longer relevant,' said Mr Phil Cole, a London
regional organiser. He has just completed an analysis of Labour's difficulty
in winning in prosperous areas of London.
A lunchtime fringe meeting, 'Did proportional representation lose Labour the
election?', offered hope of a more considered appraisal. PR was a focus of
campaigning in the last week of the election campaign.
But Mr Roy Hattersley, former deputy leader and the main speaker, was
dismissive. 'Of course PR didn't lose us the general election. We lost the
general election for a number of other reasons,' he told the thinly attended
assembly.
A frontbench spokesman, drinking late at night in the Imperial hotel, spoke
as if the election result had been a personal bereavement; he had
re-appraised his life but decided he had to go on as before. All this fuels
the impression that the 'One more heave-ers' - those believing only a little
more effort is needed for Labour to win the next election - are in the
ascendancy. But there are many willing to play on what is perhaps the
subconscious fear of many delegates: that the review of strategy, policy and
organisation has to be far-reaching.
Mr Giles Radice, the Labour MP, warned in a Fabian Society pamphlet this
week that the party needed a radical shift in policy if it was to achieve
the breakthrough in the south-east needed to defeat the Conservatives.
'There is a general view that we don't want to look back. Looking back is a
dangerous thing for a political party - but I believe it is necessary,' he
said.
The lack of open debate is partly a product of the conference format. Mr
Radice describes it as a 'sentimentalist' occasion, rather than an
institution for careful analysis. Avoiding recriminations is also a good
short-term tactic; too much introspection would only distract from turmoil
in the Conservative party. Labour's standing in opinion polls is rising,
boosting confidence and reducing the apparent need for change.
At the same time there has yet to emerge a coherent programme for
institutional or policy change that can command support among more than a
handful of members.
Even the voice of the left wing is marginalised - restricted in yesterday's
debate to one complaint that the party manifesto had been just 'capitalism
with a nice Labour face - it was political suicide,' from the Wirral West
delegate.
For many supporters of the leadership, Mr John Smith's election in July was
a change in itself. As he left the conference platform last night, it must
have been clear that the form and pace of reform will be largely up to him.
</TEXT>
