<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The Labour Party at Blackpool: Smith tightens his grip on
NEC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR TONY BLAIR, the shadow home secretary, and Mr Gordon Brown, shadow
chancellor, were elected for the first time to Labour's national executive
committee yesterday as Mr John Smith took an unshakeable grip on the party's
ruling body.
Mr Neil Kinnock - Mr Smith's predecessor as party leader - was also elected
to the 26-member committee, scoring the highest vote in the constituency
section.
Senior party officials hailed the result as a crushing endorsement of the
leadership by grass-roots supporters. In line with a rule change implemented
last year, delegates cast their votes in accordance with the results of a
ballot of constituency party members.
Following the result - which saw the ejection of Mr Dennis Skinner, MP for
Bolsover, and Mr Brian Gould, the unsuccessful challenger to Mr Smith in
Labour's leadership election earlier this year - Mr Tony Benn will be the
lone voice of left-wing dissent.
This may severely restrict the ability of the veteran Chesterfield MP to act
as a thorn in the leadership's flesh, as he may lack the routine seconder
needed to table motions.
In other respects, the result will make no obvious impact on the running of
the party, because the once left-wing NEC has long been closely identified
with the leadership.
With Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, also returned and
Mrs Margaret Beckett, deputy leader, free to continue as an ex-officio
member, Mr Smith has secured what amounts to a kitchen cabinet of senior
Westminster colleagues within Labour's ruling body.*
Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, and Mr John Prescott, shadow
transport secretary, completed the line-up of constituency representatives,
while Mr Gerald Kaufman, ex-shadow foreign secretary, did not stand for
re-election.
Mr Gould, who resigned as shadow heritage secretary on Sunday over his
opposition to the Maastricht treaty, blamed the sharp decline in his vote on
adverse reaction to his leadership challenge.
Facing the end of a 14-year NEC stint, Mr Skinner vowed to remain 'the voice
of the left in parliament'. He blamed his demise partly on not appealing to
'yuppies in the south'.
Mr Kinnock pledged to 'sustain the impetus' for democratic change within the
party. 'It is a very, very strong National Executive Committee and, most
important, a committee with the authority that comes from one member, one
vote,' he said.
In other sections, Ms Hilary Armstrong, Mr Smith's parliamentary private
secretary and another loyalist, takes Mrs Beckett's place on the women's
slate, while Ms Judith Church of MSF becomes the first woman to win outright
in the trade unions section.
With Mr Smith and Mrs Margaret Beckett, deputy leader, as ex-officio
members, the NEC comprises:
Trade union section (12 members): D. Duffy (TGWU), W. Connor (Usdaw), C.
Kelly (Ucatt), T. Sawyer (Nupe), G. Colling (GPMU), V. Hince (RMT), J.
Church (MSF), T. Clarke (UCW), D. Ward (NCU), N. Harris (AEU), R. Rosser
(TSSA), C. O'Kane (Cohse).
Constituency Labour parties (seven members): N. Kinnock, D. Blunkett, G.
Brown, J. Prescott, R. Cook, T. Blair, T. Benn.
Women (five members): J. Lestor, C. Short, D. Jeuda, H. Armstrong, B.
Etchells.
Also elected was Mr Tom Burlison of GMB as treasurer.
</TEXT>
