<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / Abta warns of flaw in new rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROPOSED government rules for package tours could result in disreputable
companies basing themselves in European Community countries with weaker
regulations, travel industry representatives warned yesterday.
The government has proposed that the regulations, due to come into effect
next year, should apply to packages sold in the UK, except when the company
offering them is established in another EC country.
Mr Keith Betton, for the Association of British Travel Agents, said: 'If the
contract is concluded in the UK, then UK legislation should be the basis of
customer protection. We think otherwise the system will be abused by
companies searching for the weakest link in the European Community chain.'
The proposed regulations are designed to implement an EC directive requiring
travel companies to ensure that they repatriate holidaymakers and return
their money if the operator collapses.
The directive leaves it up to each government to decide how the regulations
should be implemented. However, Abta is concerned that implementation of the
directive will be weaker in some member states than in others, allowing
companies to shop around until they find the least restrictive European
country in which to base themselves.
The latest version of the government's proposals, published yesterday,
offers companies three options: arranging a bond with an approved trade
association; taking out insurance in the form of policies issued to
individual customers, giving them the right to claim themselves; and opening
a designated account into which all the deposits would be paid.
Baroness Denton, consumer affairs minister, said yesterday: 'The
implementation is designed to enable each operator - and there are up to
20,000 of them - to choose which of the several options are appropriate to
their needs.'
However, Mr Betton said the regulations would be inadequate because the
government had rejected Abta's suggestion that all companies be licensed.
Mr Betton also criticised the government's proposal that companies should
only have to help tourists to return home when they are stranded while they
are taking a holiday abroad.
He said that a Scottish holidaymaker in Cornwall could find it just as
difficult to return home as someone from the south of England on holiday in
France.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
